1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 ( 3. g3 { I believe that this is the best move order to go for the Nd2 variation as it cuts down on our options. It does allow some other ideas on move 3 though. } 3... d5 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5. Nd2 { This is a more aggressive option as white is often ready to sacrifice the c4 pawn for play on the kingside and the center. } 5... O-O 6. Nf3 dxc4 7. Qc2 { The queen is well placed here along this diagonal and also keeps an eye on the c4 pawn. } ( 7. a3 { This forces us to give up our bishop on d2 but is also a non-developing move. } ) ( 7. O-O { This is a very natural move but it allows us to secure the pawn on b5. It leads to messy positions but I generally prefer to be the side with an extra pawn. } 7... b5 8. a4 c6 ) 7... a5 { We prepare the move b5 as now a4 can be met with c6. We create some space for our rook. } ) 3... d5 4. g3 { The Catalan is one of the biggest tests for black after 1.d4. white gets his bishop to g2 and it is usually a very dangerous piece in the resulting middlegames. white does not mind sacrificing the c4 pawn in return for quick development and space in the center. } 4... Bb4+ { This is my favourite response to the Catalan and it fits in perfectly with our repertoire against the Nimzo. It is one of the main lines and the point is to force one of white's minor pieces on the queenside to go to the awkward d2 square. } 5. Bd2 { This is the main move offering a trade of the dark-squared bishops which would help white's development. However. the bishop will later hinder the development of the b1 knight. } ( 5. Nc3 { has been covered in a previous database on the Nimzo indian. } ) 5... Be7 { This is the most solid square for the bishop similar to the QGD lines. We want to now castle and slowly develop our queenside. We will take on c4 only if we can hold on to the pawn comfortably. } 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O { We have two options here which will likely transpose but there are a few different independent options on the 8th move. } ( 7. Qc2 { This is another possible move order to reach the main lines but it can also be an independent option in some cases. We will see this in the first chapter. } ) 7... Nbd7 { I feel this is more flexible as we retain the option of going c7-c5 in one go. The knight can also go to b6 to defend the pawn on c4. } 8. Qc2 ( 8. Nc3 { This is a bold move giving up the pawn on c4 to go e4 and get control over the center. We will see this along with a few lines in chapter 2. } ) 8... c6 { We get a Semi-Slav type of structure which is pretty effective against the bishop on g2. Our plan next is to go b6, Ba6 or Bb7. We can also consider going for the plan of Ne4 and f5 at some point or a5-a4. Our position is pretty flexible. } 9. Rd1 { This is one of the main moves in the position and is the natural square for the rook- the other rook is likely to come to c1 in the future. We can continue with our plan of developing the light-squared bishop. } ( 9. Bf4 { It is also possible to start with this as it gives white the flexibility to put his rook on either c1 or d1. } 9... b6 10. cxd5 { I always used to want to avoid this line against lower-rated players as I felt this would lead to complete equality. However, I later realised that there is still a decent amount of play left here with the bishop on g2. It is not fully symmetrical. } 10... cxd5 11. Rc1 { If white continues normally with his development he gets absolutely nothing as the only way to create some play is along the open file. } 11... Bb7 { We have some very interesting lines coming up here. } ) ( 9. Rc1 { I never understood this plan earlier as it feels too early to commit to c1 with the rook. However, the point is that white is ready to meet b6 with cxd5 forcing us to open the 'c' file. It is not a big deal but we have several other options available. } ) 9... b6 10. Bf4 ( 10. b3 { white prepares to develop the knight to c3. Now, the logical response would be to go Ba6 but then white goes a4-a5 and it is slightly annoying. } 10... a5 $1 { We go a5 before putting our bishop on a6 avoiding white's a4-a5 plan. Now again it is not easy for white to develop his knight. } ) 10... Ba6 { The choice between Ba6 and Bb7 is not easy as both moves make sense. The bishop on a6 discourages b3, Nc3 ideas while the bishop on b7 helps prepare c5. I feel that the bishop on a6 is more active. } 11. Ne5 ( 11. cxd5 { This is not a very common move but it poses an interesting dilemma for us. } ) 11... Rc8 12. cxd5 { Now, we have a choice between the solid cxd5 and the more ambitious Nxd5. I recommend taking with the knight if you remember the details. If you feel like your opponent is very well prepared or do not remember any ideas you can take cxd5. } *[Event "?"]
