1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 { The Catalan is one of the biggest tests for black after 1.d4. white gets his bishop to g2 and it is usually a very dangerous piece in the resulting middlegames. white does not mind sacrificing the c4 pawn in return for quick development and space in the center. } 4... Bb4+ { This is my favourite response to the Catalan and it fits in perfectly with our repertoire against the Nimzo. It is one of the main lines and the point is to force one of white's minor pieces on the queenside to go to the awkward d2 square. } 5. Bd2 { This is the main move offering a trade of the dark-squared bishops which would help white's development. However. the bishop will later hinder the development of the b1 knight. } ( 5. Nc3 { This has been examined in the previous database on the Nimzo Indian. } ) 5... Be7 { This is the most solid square for the bishop similar to the QGD lines. We want to now castle and slowly develop our queenside. We will take on c4 only if we can hold on to the pawn comfortably. } ( 5... a5 { is a very interesting system which I have played a few times but it has already been recommended on Modern Chess by Roiz. It can certainly be combined with this repertoire to have two different types of options. } ) ( 5... Bd6 { is another move which I have dabbled with but it is less sound and more risky. black often jumps to e4 with the knight followed by f5. } ) 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Qc2 { This is another possible move order to reach the main lines but it can also be an independent option in some cases. } ( 7. Nc3 { The knight does not usually go to c3 in these lines and it is an indication for us to take on c4 as white cannot win it back easily. } 7... dxc4 8. Qa4 { This wastes a lot of time bringing the queen out too early. } ( 8. O-O a6 $11 { [%cal Gb7b5] } ) 8... a6 9. Qxc4 b5 10. Qd3 Bb7 11. O-O Nbd7 $11 { We will go c5 next with no problems. } ) 7... c6 8. h4 $5 { A typical modern idea pushing the 'h' pawn down the board. This has been played by a few strong players and it is not easy to face over the board- speaking with practical experience :) } 8... Nbd7 9. Nc3 ( 9. h5 { fixes the pawn structure too early } 9... h6 10. Nc3 dxc4 $15 ) 9... dxc4 { Again, we take on c4 as soon as white goes Nc3. The drawback is that it allows white to go e4 in the center and gain space. } 10. Rd1 ( 10. O-O-O { The king was much safer in the center as we can immediately start our play on the queenside. } 10... a5 $15 ) 10... Qc7 $5 { [%csl Ge5] This has been played in only two games so far. We are preparing to go for the move e5 next following the rule- play on the flank should be countered in the center. } 11. Bf4 { This is necessary but it trades off a pair of minor pieces which is in our favour. } ( 11. e4 { allows } 11... e5 $17 ) ( 11. O-O { is too slow } 11... b5 $15 ) ( 11. Ng5 { is usually a tricky move but does not work here. } 11... h6 12. Nce4 Rd8 13. Bf4 Qa5+ 14. Kf1 { 1-0 (36) Dudin,G (2475) -Kantor,G (2532) Webster Groves 2023 } 14... Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Nf6 $17 ) 11... Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. O-O { This is more clever as we are still not able to go for the move e5. Another point is that Qe7 can be met with the move Ne5 now. } ( 13. e4 Qe7 { white has to continue pushing the 'e' pawn or allow us to go e5. } 14. e5 Nd5 15. O-O ( 15. Ne4 b5 $15 { The d6 square is not that important as we can always go f6 and fight back in the center. } ) ( 15. Ng5 { is not that dangerous after } 15... f5 $1 16. Qe2 h6 17. Nh3 N7b6 18. Bxd5 cxd5 19. Nf4 Rf7 $11 20. g4 $6 fxg4 21. Qxg4 { Happened in the game 0-1 (49) Strybuk, A (2230) -Tsaruk, M (2347) Minsk 2022- } 21... Bd7 $17 ) 15... h6 { We stop ideas of Ng5 and clear the back rank. Next, we can go b5 and play on the queenside. } 16. Nd2 ( 16. Ne4 b5 17. Rfe1 ( 17. g4 f5 $17 ) 17... a5 18. g4 ( 18. a3 Ba6 $15 ) 18... Nf4 19. g5 f5 $15 ) 16... b5 17. Nde4 a5 18. Nd6 N7b6 19. Nce4 Nb4 20. Qb1 f5 { Another typical idea when the knight is on d6. We want to get back control over the center. } 21. exf6 gxf6 22. Nxc8 Raxc8 23. Nc5 f5 24. Rfe1 Rf6 25. a3 N4d5 $11 { We have some weaknesses but also an extra pawn and an outpost for the knight on c5. } ) 13... h6 { We play a useful waiting move on the kingside. We want to wait for white to go e4 before we go Qe7 and try to get the move e5. After he plays e4, Ne5 becomes much less effective as the pawn on e4 restricts white's pieces. } ( 13... Qe7 $6 14. Ne5 $14 ) 14. e4 ( 14. Rfe1 Rb8 15. e4 Qe7 { transposes. } ) 14... Qe7 { We have the option to go e5 now but we can also delay it and play on the queenside. } 15. Rfe1 Rb8 { Another flexible waiting move preparing to go b5 next. We get the rook out of the dangerous diagonal and support the pawn on b5. } ( 15... b5 { is too early } 16. d5 $16 ) ( 15... e5 { is possible but I am hesitant about opening up the center with white's pieces well placed to deal with it. } 16. Ne2 exd4 17. Nexd4 Nb6 18. e5 { This is objectively fine for us but I would be worried in a practical game seeing the activity of white's pieces. } 18... Nfd5 19. a3 Nc7 ( 19... Rd8 20. e6 $14 ) 20. Nd2 Rd8 21. Nxc4 { white wins back the pawn but we do manage to get enough activity to counter it. } 21... Bg4 22. f3 Nxc4 23. Qxc4 Be6 24. Qc2 g6 25. f4 Bg4 $11 { There will be a few trades now and the position simplifies. } ) 16. e5 ( 16. d5 e5 $1 { We keep the center closed and white has to work hard to prove his compensation for the pawn. } 17. Bf1 Nb6 18. d6 Qe6 19. Na4 Nfd7 20. Nxb6 Nxb6 21. Qc3 Re8 22. Re3 Bd7 $11 { We have an extra pawn and easier play in my opinion. We can bring our rook to d8 and go for c5, Ba6. } ) 16... Nd5 17. Ne4 ( 17. g4 { A super risky move due to } 17... f5 $1 { We will now start playing on the kingside trying to exploit the weaknesses created by white. } 18. exf6 N7xf6 $11 ) 17... b5 18. b3 ( 18. g4 { This is a very dangerous move to play as it gives up full control over the f4 square. } 18... Nf4 19. Qd2 Nxg2 20. Kxg2 f5 $15 { A very typical move to open up the 'f' file and get some activity for our pieces. } ) 18... Nb4 19. Qd2 Nd3 20. Re2 c5 { We want to open up the position to finish our development. } 21. Nd6 cxd4 22. bxc4 bxc4 23. Nxc4 Nb4 { The bishop will come out to a6 next and we have no issues regarding development. } 24. Qxd4 Ba6 $11 *[Event "?"]
