1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O { We have two options here which will likely transpose but there are a few different independent options on the 8th move. } 7... Nbd7 { I feel this is more flexible as we retain the option of going c7-c5 in one go. The knight can also go to b6 to defend the pawn on c4. } 8. Nc3 { This is a bold move giving up the pawn on c4 to go e4 and get control over the center. } ( 8. Na3 { is a very weird move misplacing the knight. } 8... Ne4 9. Rc1 Nxd2 10. Nxd2 c6 $11 ) ( 8. a4 { has been played in many different positions but I feel that it mainly creates a weakness on b4. } 8... a5 9. Na3 ( 9. Qc2 { transposes to the next chapter after } 9... c6 ) 9... c6 10. Rc1 Nb6 11. Ne5 Nfd7 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 $11 ) ( 8. b3 { This is pretty slow preparing the move Nc3. } 8... b6 9. Nc3 ( 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nc3 Re8 11. Rc1 Bb7 $11 ) 9... Bb7 10. Rc1 Rc8 { We are ready to take on c4 next and go for the move c5. } 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Qc2 c5 $11 ) ( 8. b4 { This has been played by a few strong players. white wants to gain maximum space on the queenside and not allow us to fight back easily. } 8... b6 { This particular move has never been played but it will transpose back. We are now ready to take on c4 next followed by Bb7. } ( 8... dxc4 9. Qc1 b5 10. a4 $14 ) 9. a4 { a5 is now a serious threat. } ( 9. Qc2 { white defends c4 and prepares to bring his rook to c1. The a1 rook can be used to play along the 'a' file. } 9... c6 10. Rc1 Ba6 { We want to either force white to release the tension or put his knight on the rim. } ( 10... a5 { was premature in my game- 1/2-1/2 (56) Pantzar, M (2441) -Arjun, K (2537) Castelldefels 2021. } ) 11. Na3 Bb7 { Job done we now are threatening to go a5. } 12. Qb3 h6 13. Rab1 Re8 14. c5 Bf8 $11 { We will go either Ne4 or e5 next and fight back in the center. } ) 9... c6 { [%cal Ga7a5] } 10. Qc2 ( 10. a5 Ba6 $15 ) 10... Ne4 { This happened in my game. } ( 10... a5 { is also good. We immediately stop any queenside expansion. } 11. bxa5 bxa5 12. c5 Ne4 13. Be3 f5 { This is the exact kind of position we want to get here. We have the chance to create some play on the kingside with g5 and h5. } 14. Nbd2 Ba6 15. Nb3 Bf6 16. Rab1 h5 17. h4 { white is ready to go Bf4 next. } 17... e5 $11 { We break in the center just in time. } ) 11. b5 ( 11. Be1 a5 $1 12. bxa5 bxa5 $11 { [%cal Gf7f5,Gc8a6] } ) 11... Bb7 12. Nc3 ( 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Bc1 Rc8 { black took over easily in the game Salimova, N (2353) -Arjun, K (2532) Cattolica 2022 but I ended up blundering badly at the end. } ) 12... Nxc3 13. Bxc3 ( 13. Qxc3 c5 $11 ) 13... dxc4 { white sacrifices the pawn to open the long diagonal. } 14. bxc6 Bxc6 15. Ng5 Bxg5 16. Bxc6 Rc8 $11 ) ( 8. Bf4 { is too early here. } 8... dxc4 { In addition to winning the pawn on c4 we are also able to get control over the d5 square with Nd5 next attacking the bishop on f4. } 9. Qc2 ( 9. a4 Nd5 $11 ) ( 9. Nbd2 b5 $1 10. Ne5 Nxe5 { We can give up the exchange in return for a pawn and active pieces. } 11. Bxa8 Ng6 12. e3 Nd5 $15 ) 9... Nd5 10. Qxc4 { white unfortunately has to give up his bishop on f4. } 10... Nxf4 11. gxf4 Nb6 12. Qc2 Kh8 13. e3 f6 { We will eventually start our play in the center or the queenside. } 14. Nc3 c6 $11 ) ( 8. Qb3 { white defends the pawn on c4 and gets ready to go Nc3 next. There is a very typical idea to meet the move Qb3. } 8... a5 $1 { We want to kick the queen back quickly. } 9. Bf4 ( 9. Rd1 c6 10. Bf4 a4 11. Qc2 h6 $11 { [%cal Gf8e8] We play our useful waiting moves and white lacks a good plan. } ) ( 9. Nc3 { does not achieve much since after } 9... c6 10. Rfd1 a4 $1 { we can go a4 anyway. } 11. Nxa4 dxc4 12. Qc2 b5 13. Nc3 Bb7 14. e4 h6 15. a4 b4 16. e5 Nd5 17. Ne4 c5 $11 { We open up the position breaking in the center. } ) 9... a4 { The pawn on a4 is definitely in our favour. It helps us get control of the 'a' file. } 10. Qc2 dxc4 { This is typical with the bishop on f4 since we can go Nd5 with a tempo. } 11. Qxc4 Nd5 { We can go for the move b5 next followed by Ba6. We are ahead of white in development and activity. } 12. a3 { 1/2-1/2 (55) Yuffa,D (2582) -Fressinet,L (2652) Skopje 2019 } ( 12. Qc2 b5 13. Nc3 Nxf4 14. gxf4 Bb7 15. Nxb5 Ra5 $11 { [%cal Gd8a8] We have tremendous compensation with the bishop pair and active pieces. } ) ( 12. Bd2 b5 $1 13. Qc6 ( 13. Qxb5 Ba6 $11 ) 13... Rb8 14. Rd1 Nc5 $1 15. dxc5 Bd7 16. Qa6 Ra8 $11 ) ( 12. Nc3 N7b6 13. Qd3 Nxf4 14. gxf4 a3 $11 ) 12... b5 $1 13. Qc6 Rb8 $11 { [%cal Gb8b6,Gc8b7] } ) 8... dxc4 { Of course, we do not shy away from a fight. } 9. e4 ( 9. Qa4 { Is rarely a good idea to waste so much time with the queen. } 9... a6 10. Qxc4 b5 11. Qd3 Bb7 $11 ) 9... b5 $1 { We are happy to give up the b5 pawn to get back control over the center. } 10. e5 ( 10. Nxb5 Nxe4 { white has to be careful not to get worse here as he is down a pawn with just temporary activity in return. } 11. Ba5 ( 11. Ne5 Bb7 12. Ba5 Qc8 13. Nxc4 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Qb7+ $11 ) ( 11. Qc2 Rb8 12. Nxa7 Bb7 $11 ) 11... Nb6 12. Ne5 ( 12. Qe2 Nd6 $15 ) 12... Bb7 13. Qc2 ( 13. Qe2 Qd5 $11 ) 13... Nd6 { The position will simplify now with a lot of exchanges. } 14. Bxb7 Nxb7 15. Bxb6 cxb6 16. Qxc4 Nd6 17. Nxd6 Qxd6 $11 ) 10... Nd5 11. Nxb5 { white has won back the pawn but we get the semi-open 'b' file and activity in return. We will play on the queenside keeping the d5 square under control. } 11... a5 12. Qe2 ( 12. Qc2 N7b6 13. a3 ( 13. Nc3 Bb7 $11 ) 13... Bb7 14. Nc3 ( 14. Rfe1 Qd7 ) 14... Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Bd5 { The bishop is very well placed on d5 and we will go for c5 soon. } 16. Nd2 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Qd5+ 18. Kg1 Rfd8 $11 ) 12... a4 $1 { The c4 pawn is not hanging since we have Ba6. We might go for a3 soon. } ( 12... Bb7 13. h4 a4 14. Rfc1 Rb8 15. Ng5 h6 16. Ne4 c5 17. Qg4 Kh8 18. Qh5 Nb4 19. Nbd6 Bxd6 20. exd6 Bxe4 21. Bxe4 Nf6 22. Qe5 { 1/2-1/2 (22) Abolins Abols,D (2356) -Gutierrez Dopino,J (2347) ICCF email 2020 } ) 13. a3 ( 13. Qxc4 N7b6 14. Qc2 Ba6 $15 ) 13... c5 $1 { We are undermining white's control over the center. We have a firm grip on the queenside with Qb6 to follow. } 14. Rfd1 Qb6 15. Nd6 { white decides to give up his e5 pawn but wants to win our dark-squared bishop. } ( 15. Nc3 Bb7 16. Qxc4 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Nxe5 $11 ) 15... Ba6 16. Bc3 Rad8 { There is no rush to win the pawn on d6 as it does give white some counterplay. } 17. Qc2 Nxc3 18. bxc3 cxd4 19. cxd4 Bxd6 20. Rab1 { white tries to gain a quick tempo against our queen but he is in for a rude shock! } ( 20. exd6 Qxd6 21. Qxa4 Rc8 $11 ) 20... Qb3 $1 { We give up our queen but get strong connected pawns. } 21. Rxb3 axb3 22. Qc3 Nxe5 $1 23. Nd2 Be7 24. dxe5 Rd3 $11 { [%cal Gc4c3] } *[Event "?"]
