1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Qc2 { This is the main move in the position keeping an eye on the c4 pawn. The question remains how white is going to develop the b1 knight? } 8... c6 { We get a Semi-Slav type of structure which is pretty effective against the bishop on g2. Our plan next is to go b6, Ba6 or Bb7. We can also consider going for the plan of Ne4 and f5 at some point or a5-a4. Our position is pretty flexible. } 9. Rc1 { I never understood this plan earlier as it feels too early to commit to c1 with the rook. However, the point is that white is ready to meet b6 with cxd5 forcing us to open the 'c' file. It is not a big deal but we have several other options available. } ( 9. b3 { This is a slow way of getting the knight to c3. } 9... b6 10. Bc3 { The bishop is worse here on c3 compared to b2. } ( 10. Nc3 Ba6 { We immediately go after the c4 pawn forcing white to release the tension. } 11. Bf4 dxc4 12. Nd2 cxb3 13. axb3 Bb7 $11 ) 10... Bb7 11. Nbd2 c5 { We have equalised comfortably here. } 12. dxc5 ( 12. Rfd1 Rc8 13. Qb2 dxc4 14. Nxc4 b5 $11 { [%cal Gb5b4] } ) 12... Bxc5 { We have a nice square on e7 for our queen. } 13. Qb2 Rc8 14. a3 Re8 $5 15. b4 Bf8 $11 ) ( 9. a4 { We saw something very similar in the previous chapter. } 9... a5 { We are happy to fix the weakness on b4. } 10. Rc1 { white is playing useful moves without committing to a plan to develop the knight. He wants to meet b6 with cd5 forcing us to recapture with the 'c' pawn. } ( 10. cxd5 exd5 { This is a great structure for us with the semi-open 'e' file. } 11. Nc3 Bb4 $11 ) ( 10. Bf4 b6 11. cxd5 ( 11. Nbd2 Nh5 12. Be3 Ba6 $11 ) 11... Nxd5 { We give up a pawn for activity and development. } 12. Qxc6 Ba6 13. Qc2 Rc8 14. Nc3 N7f6 { It is not going to be easy to defend c3. white will have to give up one of his pawns back soon. } 15. Rfc1 Bb4 16. Bd2 Bxe2 $11 ) ( 10. Na3 Bd6 { [%cal Gd8e7] The knight is just misplaced on a3. } 11. Ne1 Re8 12. Nd3 e5 $1 { We time the break perfectly as the knight on d3 helps us get a tempo. } 13. cxd5 ( 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 $11 ) 13... e4 $1 14. Nf4 cxd5 { black was slightly better in the game 1/2-1/2 (60) Ding, L (2805) -Anand, V (2756) Saint Louis 2019. } ) 10... Ne4 { This is the most direct plan to start our play on the Kingside. } ( 10... h6 $5 { This is more cunning, waiting for white to decide on a plan. } 11. Be1 ( 11. Na3 Ne4 12. Be3 Bb4 $11 ) ( 11. Bf4 Re8 12. Nbd2 Bb4 $11 { [%cal Gc6c5] } ) 11... b6 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nc3 Ba6 14. Nb5 Rc8 15. Qd1 Rxc1 16. Rxc1 Qb8 17. e3 Rc8 $11 ) 11. Be1 ( 11. Be3 b6 { With the knight on e5 we do not mind opening the 'c' file. } 12. cxd5 cxd5 $11 ) ( 11. Ne1 Nxd2 $1 { We change our plans as we can prepare the e5 break now that the knight has gone away from f3. } ( 11... f5 12. Nd3 $14 ) 12. Nxd2 Bf6 13. e3 e5 $11 { The bishop is going to get activated soon. } ) 11... f5 12. Nc3 ( 12. e3 g5 $11 { [%cal Gh7h5,Ge7d6] black had a great position in the game 1/2-1/2 (38) Ganguly,S (2627) -Warmerdam,M (2607) Wijk aan Zee 2022. } ) 12... Bd6 ( 12... g5 { may actually be a better move order } 13. e3 ( 13. Na2 g4 14. Nd2 Rf7 $15 { [%cal Gd8f8,Gh7h5] } ) 13... Bd6 14. Nd2 Nxd2 15. Bxd2 Nf6 $11 ) 13. Na2 g5 $1 { Once we have started our play we cannot shy away from the critical moves. } 14. b4 g4 15. Nh4 ( 15. Nd2 axb4 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Nxb4 c5 $1 18. dxc5 Bxc5 { black took over the initiative in the game 1/2-1/2 (93) Jumabayev,R (2630) -Eljanov,P (2663) Douglas 2019. We ca go h5-h4 next. } ) 15... Be7 16. bxa5 Bxh4 17. gxh4 Qxh4 18. f4 Qh6 19. e3 Ndf6 $11 { We want to go g3 next followed by Ng4. } ) 9... a5 $5 { We have seen this a few times before and we are just improving our position slowly. } ( 9... b6 10. cxd5 cxd5 { This should also be fine for us but we do not need to allow this. } ) 10. Bf4 ( 10. e3 b5 $1 { is a good idea forcing white to release the tension. } 11. cxb5 cxb5 12. Bf1 Ba6 13. a3 { white is preparing to go for the move b4 next. } 13... Ne4 ( 13... Bd6 { Happened in the game 1/2-1/2 (28) Sargsyan, S (2639) -Gukesh, D (2629) Dusseldorf 2023 but white has some pressure after } 14. b4 $5 axb4 15. Bxb4 { [%cal Gb1c3] } ) 14. Be1 a4 $11 { Next, we will continue with Nb6-c4 with a comfortable position. } ) ( 10. a3 { white keeps making slow waiting moves. } 10... b6 { Now it is a better version for us. } 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Bf4 Ba6 13. Nc3 Nh5 { We kick the bishop away from its active post on f4. } ( 13... b5 { is also possible } 14. a4 $5 ( 14. e3 Qb6 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (39) Ding,L (2799) -Carlsen,M (2847) chess24.com INT 2021 } ) 14... bxa4 15. Qxa4 Nh5 ( 15... Bb4 $11 ) 16. Bc7 $14 { white was better in the game 1-0 (46) Wojtaszek, R (2708) -Cardoso Cardoso, J (2493) Chennai 2022. } ) ( 13... h6 $5 14. h4 ( 14. Qa4 g5 15. Be3 Kg7 $11 ) 14... b5 { This inclusion works well for black as it has created some weaknesses in white's kingside. } 15. a4 bxa4 16. Qxa4 Bb4 17. Na2 Bxe2 18. Nxb4 axb4 19. Qxb4 Rxa1 20. Rxa1 Qc8 $11 ) 14. Bd2 ( 14. Be5 Rc8 15. Qd1 Nhf6 $11 { Now both Ne4 and Nxe5 are an issue for white. } ) 14... Nhf6 { We come back and ask our opponent how he wants to improve his position. There are other ways too to keep the game going. } 15. Qb3 Ne4 $11 ) 10... h6 { We cover the g5 square and create the potential idea of going for the move g5. The bishop is not very stable on f4. } 11. Nbd2 { The most logical developing move. } ( 11. h4 { creates a hole in the kingside which we exploit with } 11... Ng4 $14 { [%cal Gf7f5,Gg7g5] } 12. Nbd2 g5 $15 ) ( 11. a3 a4 { The typical response, getting a favourable pawn structure on the queenside and stopping b4. } 12. Bd2 ( 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 { black was already better in the game 1/2-1/2 (21) Istratescu,A (2361) -Kantor,G (2527) Arad 2023 after } 13... Ng4 14. Bf4 dxc4 $15 15. Qxc4 Qb6 $17 { [%csl Rb2,Rd4] } ) 12... b5 $1 { We have already seen a similar idea before. We will follow up with Nb6-c4 quickly. } 13. cxb5 cxb5 14. Nc3 Ba6 15. Na2 { white is ready to meet Nb6 with Ba5 but we can also go } 15... Ne4 16. Be1 Nd6 $11 { [%csl Gc4] } ) 11... g5 $1 { We can hunt down the dark-squared bishop now! } 12. Be3 Ng4 { We execute our idea, winning the dark-squared bishop by force. Next, we can continue playing on the kingside with our king secure on the dark-squares. } 13. Nf1 Nxe3 14. Nxe3 h5 15. h3 Kg7 16. Qd3 ( 16. Bh1 Rh8 17. Qd3 Nf8 $15 { black went on to convert in the game 0-1 (61) Ziechaus, L (2106) -Bowley, M ICCF email 2021. } ) 16... Rh8 17. cxd5 cxd5 18. Rc3 Nf8 $11 { black is the one with the initiative in my opinion. We can also go b5 on the queenside. } *[Event "?"]
