1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Qc2 c6 9. Rd1 { This is one of the main moves in the position and is the natural square for the rook- the other rook is likely to come to c1 in the future. We can continue with our plan of developing the light-squared bishop. } 9... b6 ( 9... a5 { This does not make as much sense here as white can go for play in the center with the rook on d1. } 10. Bf4 h6 11. Ne5 { [%csl Rd8] } ) 10. b3 { white prepares to develop the knight to c3. Now, the logical response would be to go Ba6 but then white goes a4-a5 and it is slightly annoying. } ( 10. Bf4 { We will be analysing this in the upcoming chapters. } ) ( 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. Bc3 Qc7 13. f4 Ba6 $15 { Was slightly better for black in the game 1/2-1/2 (47) Onischuk,A (2682) -Wojtaszek,R (2745) Tbilisi 2017. } ) ( 10. a4 { Is not particularly impressive here with the rook on d1. } 10... a5 11. cxd5 ( 11. Bf4 { Happened in the game 1-0 (49) Caruana,F (2782) -Alekseev,E (2573) Chess.com INT 2023 but black is doing very well after } 11... Ba6 $11 ) ( 11. b3 Ba6 $11 ) 11... cxd5 12. Nc3 Ba6 13. Nb5 Ne4 14. Qb3 Rc8 $11 { [%cal Ge4d6] } ) 10... a5 $1 { We go a5 before putting our bishop on a6 avoiding white's a4-a5 plan. Now again it is not easy for white to develop his knight. } ( 10... Ba6 11. a4 $1 ) 11. Bc3 { white is ready to go Nbd2 and e4 next. However, we are just in time with- } ( 11. Nc3 Ba6 $11 { [%csl Rc4] } ) ( 11. Bf4 Ba6 12. Nbd2 ( 12. Ne5 Rc8 $11 ) 12... Nh5 13. Be3 Rc8 { We have the idea to go f5-f4 next. white has to be careful. } 14. Ne5 Nhf6 15. Ndf3 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Re8 $11 { We will continue slowly with Bd6 and h6. I do not see a good plan for white. } ) 11... Ne4 $1 { We shift plans and get our knight to the active e4 post. white has wasted time with his bishop. However, keep in mind that we are not going to go f5 blindly next. } ( 11... Bb7 { is also not bad } 12. Nbd2 Qc7 13. e4 ( 13. Rac1 c5 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Qb2 Rfd8 16. a3 dxc4 17. Nxc4 Bd5 $11 ) 13... dxe4 14. Nxe4 c5 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Rd2 ( 16. d5 exd5 17. cxd5 Rad8 $11 ) 16... cxd4 17. Bxd4 Rad8 18. Rad1 h6 $11 ) 12. Bb2 ( 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxe4 { This looks strong but we have the nice resource- } 13... f5 $1 14. Bg2 ( 14. Bxf5 Rxf5 15. dxe5 Qe8 $15 { The light squares are a big issue on the kingside. } ) 14... Ng4 15. Nd2 f4 { The benefit of our pawn structure in the center is that it keeps the position semi closed and allows us to play more freely on the kingside. } 16. Nf3 fxg3 17. hxg3 Bd6 $11 ) ( 12. Nbd2 { gives up the bishop very easily. } 12... Nxc3 13. Qxc3 Bb7 $11 ) 12... f5 { With the bishop on b2 it makes perfect sense to start our play on the kingside. f4 also becomes an idea for us. } 13. Nc3 Qe8 $1 { The queen prepares to head over to the kingside soon. } 14. e3 ( 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 h5 $1 { [%cal Gh5h4] } ) 14... Ba6 15. Ne5 Rc8 16. Ne2 g5 { This is more of a prophylactic measure against Nf4 ideas. We cannot immediately go all in on the kingside. We should take our time and even look at doing something on the queenside in between. } 17. f3 Nef6 18. Rac1 b5 19. cxb5 Bxb5 20. Qd2 Bb4 { We trade a few pieces now. Ideally, we would love to play with our knight against the bishop on g2. } 21. Bc3 Nxe5 22. dxe5 Bxe2 23. Qxe2 Bxc3 24. Rxc3 Nd7 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (37) Ludgate,A (2513) -Germanes,R (2518) FICGS email 2022 } *[Event "?"]
