1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Qc2 c6 9. Bf4 { It is also possible to start with this as it gives white the flexibility to put his rook on either c1 or d1. } 9... b6 10. cxd5 { I always used to want to avoid this line against lower-rated players as I felt this would lead to complete equality. However, I later realised that there is still a decent amount of play left here with the bishop on g2. It is not fully symmetrical. } ( 10. Rd1 { We will be analysing this in the upcoming chapters. } ) ( 10. Nc3 dxc4 { The usual grabbing the pawn on c4 and getting the d5 square for the knight. } 11. Nd2 Nd5 12. Nxc4 Ba6 13. Qa4 ( 13. Ne5 { We will see similar positions in the main line but the typical idea here is to go- } 13... Nxe5 14. Bxe5 f6 $1 15. Nxd5 { We managed to force this trade which gives us a completely even position. } 15... cxd5 16. Bf4 g5 $11 ) 13... Nxf4 14. gxf4 Bxc4 { We give up the bishop pair voluntarily as the bishop would otherwise be stuck defending the pawn on c6. } 15. Qxc4 Rc8 $11 ) ( 10. Nbd2 Nh5 $1 { This is a frequent response when white has blocked the retreat for the bishop. } 11. e3 { This has been played a few times by Anish Giri. white is ready to give up the dark-squared bishop but wants to improve his pawn structure. } ( 11. cxd5 Nxf4 $1 12. dxc6 Nxg2 13. cxd7 Qxd7 14. Kxg2 Bb7 $44 { We have tremendous compensation with the unopposed bishops. } ) ( 11. Be5 Bb7 12. cxd5 ( 12. e4 Rc8 13. Rfe1 g5 $36 { [%csl Re5] Now f6 is a big threat. } ) 12... exd5 { This is the more fighting option and it works well here because the bishop is on e5. } ( 12... cxd5 { is also okay but more passive. } 13. Rfc1 Rc8 $11 ) 13. e4 Rc8 14. Rfe1 ( 14. Qa4 a6 15. exd5 cxd5 16. Qb3 f6 17. Bf4 Nxf4 18. gxf4 Bd6 $11 ) 14... c5 $1 { We open up the position for our pieces. We can win the dark-squared bishop at our leisure. } 15. exd5 cxd4 16. Qd3 Bxd5 $11 ) ( 11. Be3 Bb7 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Rfc1 Nhf6 ( 13... Bd6 14. Bg5 f6 15. Be3 f5 16. Bg5 Qe8 17. e3 h6 18. Bf4 Nxf4 19. exf4 Nf6 $11 ) 14. Bf4 Rc8 15. Qd1 Rxc1 16. Rxc1 Qa8 $11 ) 11... Bb7 { Now we are threatening the move g5 trapping the bishop. } ( 11... g5 $6 12. Be5 f6 13. cxd5 $16 ) 12. cxd5 exd5 ( 12... Nxf4 { is the more tempting move but there is no hurry yet. We want to keep the idea of g5 in the air. } 13. exf4 cxd5 14. Rfc1 Bd6 ( 14... Rc8 15. Qd1 Rxc1 16. Rxc1 Qb8 $11 { 0-1 (58) Giri,A (2764) -Van Foreest,J (2682) chess24.com INT 2020 } ) 15. Bf1 Nf6 16. Bd3 Qe7 17. Re1 Rfc8 ( 17... Rac8 18. Qd1 Qd8 19. Qe2 Rc7 20. a3 g6 21. Ne5 Qe7 22. h4 Rfc8 23. Rad1 Qf8 24. Qf3 Nh5 25. Nf1 Ng7 26. Ne3 { 1-0 (51) Giri,A (2731) -Anand,V (2751) Zagreb, Croatia 2021 } 26... h5 $11 ) 18. Qd1 Qd8 19. Ne5 Rc7 20. h4 g6 21. Qe2 h5 22. Rac1 Rac8 23. Rxc7 Rxc7 24. Kg2 Qe8 25. Ndf3 Ne4 $11 ) 13. h4 { white wastes a move to stop the idea of g5. } ( 13. Rac1 g5 $5 ( 13... c5 $11 ) 14. g4 Nxf4 15. exf4 f5 $5 { Having the bishop pair we can look to create something on the kingside, especially on the dark squares. } 16. gxf5 gxf4 $11 { [%cal Gc6c5,Ge7f6] } ) 13... c5 { As we are going to win the bishop pair soon it makes sense to try and open the position. } 14. Nb1 { The knight is better placed on c3 but it also wastes valuable time allowing us to bring all our pieces into the game. } ( 14. Rfe1 Re8 15. Rac1 ( 15. Rad1 Rc8 $11 ) 15... Rc8 16. Qd1 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Rxc1 18. Qxc1 Nxf4 19. exf4 Bc5 $11 ) 14... Nxf4 ( 14... b5 $5 15. Ng5 g6 16. Nc3 cxd4 17. Nxd5 Rc8 18. Qd3 Bxd5 19. Bxd5 Ndf6 20. Bb3 dxe3 21. Qxe3 Bc5 22. Qf3 Nxf4 23. Qxf4 a5 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (50) Tinjaca Ramirez,L (2388) -Jakubcin,M (2437) ICCF email 2021 } ) 15. exf4 cxd4 16. Nxd4 Rc8 17. Nc3 Bb4 { We will create a weakness on c3 and bring our knight to e4 next. } 18. Rfd1 ( 18. Rad1 Re8 { This is more precise it seems compared to the direct Nf6 but it is too deep. } ( 18... Nf6 19. Ndb5 a6 20. Qb3 { [%csl Rd5] } 20... Bc5 { should still be fine. } ) 19. Ndb5 Bxc3 20. bxc3 Nf6 21. Nxa7 Rc5 $11 { [%csl Ra7] } ) 18... Nf6 19. Qa4 ( 19. Ndb5 a6 20. Qb3 Bc5 $11 { f2 is a big problem here. } ) 19... a5 { b5 square is not something that white can exploit. } 20. Rac1 Rc4 21. Qb5 Qc7 22. Bf1 Rc5 23. Qd3 Ne4 24. Ncb5 Qd8 25. Rb1 Rc4 26. b3 Rc8 $11 ) 10... cxd5 11. Rc1 { If white continues normally with his development he gets absolutely nothing as the only way to create some play is along the open file. } ( 11. Bc7 Qe8 12. Rc1 Bb7 { transposes } ) ( 11. Nc3 Bb7 12. Rfc1 Rc8 13. Qb3 ( 13. Qd1 Ne4 $11 ) ( 13. Qa4 a6 $11 ) 13... a6 { We want to go b5 and maybe Nb6 next. } 14. a4 h6 { This is a useful waiting move asking white how he wants to improve his position. } 15. Na2 Rxc1+ 16. Rxc1 Qa8 { [%cal Gf8c8] } 17. Ne5 Rc8 18. Rxc8+ Qxc8 { 1/2-1/2 (20) Ludevid I Massana,J (2316) -Tauscher,K (2348) ICCF email 2019 } ) 11... Bb7 12. Bc7 ( 12. Qb3 { allows the simple } 12... Rc8 13. Rxc8 Qxc8 14. Nc3 a6 { Our next moves are likely to be Qa8, Rc8 followed by b5 and Nb6. } 15. Rc1 Qa8 16. Na4 { white wants to get his knight to c5 but it does not achieve much. } 16... b5 17. Nc5 Nxc5 ( 17... Rc8 { is a safe move. } 18. Nxb7 Qxb7 $11 ) 18. dxc5 d4 { The c5 pawn is pretty weak now. } 19. Be5 ( 19. a4 Bd5 20. Qd3 bxa4 21. Qxd4 Rc8 22. Qxa4 Rxc5 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (30) Wojtaszek,R (2749) -Ding,L (2816) Shenzhen 2018 } ) 19... Rd8 20. Bxd4 Rxd4 21. Nxd4 Bxg2 22. Nxe6 ( 22. c6 Bd5 23. c7 Qc8 $11 ) 22... fxe6 23. Qxe6+ Kf8 24. f3 Bxf3 25. exf3 Qxf3 26. b4 Bd8 27. Re1 Qc3 28. Re2 Qd4+ 29. Kg2 a5 30. a3 axb4 31. axb4 Qd3 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (31) Szczepankiewicz,D (2421) -Gorzkiewicz,L (2421) ICCF email 2018 } ) 12... Qe8 13. Qb3 { white's idea is to go Na3-b5 next and create some play on the queenside. He would love to win our dark-squared bishop with Nd6. We have to be a bit precise. } ( 13. Nc3 { The knight blocks the 'c' file unnecessarily. } 13... Rc8 14. Nb5 Nc5 $1 { This is a much stronger version compared to the main line. } 15. a4 Na6 16. Qb3 Nxc7 17. Nxc7 Qd8 $11 { black has the better chances here with the bishop pair. } ) 13... Rc8 14. Na3 { [%csl Ga7,Gd6][%cal Ga3b5] } ( 14. Nbd2 Nb8 { We get Nc6 next and the bishop has to retreat back. } 15. Be5 Nc6 $11 ) 14... Ne4 15. Nb5 Ndc5 $1 { The is a very interesting piece sacrifice exploiting white's lack of co-ordination. } 16. dxc5 bxc5 { The threat now is to go c4 and win the knight on b5. Also, Bc6 or a6 are quite dangerous. white has two ways to retreat with the bishop. } 17. Bf4 ( 17. Be5 c4 18. Qa4 f6 19. Bd4 e5 { I love this position! We get a huge advantage in the center and are likely to win back the piece on b5. } 20. Bxa7 Nd6 21. Nc3 Qxa4 22. Nxa4 Ra8 { white loses a piece and he has to start playing in defence. } 23. Bc5 Rxa4 24. Nd2 { There are a few different ways to continue here. The pawn on c4 is hanging right now. } 24... Rb8 ( 24... Rc8 25. Bxd6 Bxd6 26. b3 Ra7 27. bxc4 Bb4 $11 ) 25. e4 dxe4 26. Bxd6 Bxd6 27. Nxc4 Bc5 28. Nxe5 Bd4 29. Nd7 Rba8 30. Rc7 Bd5 31. Rd1 Bxa2 32. Bxe4 Bxf2+ 33. Kxf2 Rxe4 $11 ) 17... c4 18. Qa4 { I reached this position in a Titled Tuesday game but got confused with less time. } 18... Bc5 { We go after the pawn on f2 and now Bc6 is a huge threat. } ( 18... Bc6 $2 { allows } 19. Nfd4 Bc5 20. Nxc6 $18 { 1-0 (46) Svane,R (2637) -Arjun,K (2532) Chess.com INT 2022 } ) 19. b3 ( 19. Be3 { also does not change much. } 19... Bc6 20. Nfd4 ( 20. Bxc5 Bxb5 21. Qxa7 Nxc5 $11 ) 20... Bxd4 21. Bxd4 Bxb5 22. Qxa7 Ra8 23. Qc7 f6 { The rook will join the game via f7 next. } 24. Bxe4 dxe4 25. Bc3 { 1/2-1/2 (31) Lazavik,D (2553) -Sadhwani,R (2603) Chess.com INT 2023 } 25... e5 $11 { [%cal Ge8c6] } ) 19... Bc6 20. bxc4 dxc4 21. Qxc4 Bxf2+ 22. Kf1 e5 $1 { There are a lot of tactics in the air here. } 23. Nxe5 ( 23. Bg5 Bb6 24. Qb4 Qe6 25. Rxc6 Qxc6 26. Nxe5 Qc5 27. Qxc5 Rxc5 ) 23... Nd2+ 24. Bxd2 Bxg2+ 25. Kxf2 Rxc4 26. Nxc4 Qxb5 27. Kxg2 Rc8 $11 { The endgame is roughly balanced with white's lead in material compensated by his weak king. } *[Event "?"]
