1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Qc2 c6 9. Rd1 { This is one of the main moves in the position and is the natural square for the rook- the other rook is likely to come to c1 in the future. We can continue with our plan of developing the light-squared bishop. } 9... b6 10. Bf4 Ba6 { The choice between Ba6 and Bb7 is not easy as both moves make sense. The bishop on a6 discourages b3, Nc3 ideas while the bishop on b7 helps prepare c5. I feel that the bishop on a6 is more active. } 11. cxd5 { This is not a very common move but it poses an interesting dilemma for us which we will see soon. } ( 11. Nbd2 { as usual is met with } 11... Nh5 $1 12. Be3 ( 12. e3 Rc8 { is similar to what we have seen before } 13. h4 Bb7 { We are ready to go c5 next. } 14. Ne5 c5 15. cxd5 exd5 $11 ) 12... Rc8 13. Rac1 h6 14. Ne5 Nhf6 { The threat is to take on e5 and go Ng4. } 15. h3 Bb7 16. Qa4 a5 { We have already seen in a few cases that white cannot exploit the weakness on b5. } 17. Ndf3 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Bd6 19. Qb3 c5 $1 { This looks a bit scary but we exploit the shaky knight on e5. } 20. Ng4 Nxg4 21. hxg4 cxd4 22. Bxd4 Rxc4 { time to simplify! } 23. Rxc4 dxc4 24. Qxb6 Bxg2 25. Qxd8 Rxd8 $11 ) ( 11. b3 { This plan is more effective with the bishop on b7 but it should be checked here too. } 11... Rc8 12. Nc3 h6 { What is the point of this move? Sometimes such questions can be hard to answer :) The usual reason behind these moves is that we wait for white to show his hand. h6 is always useful for us. Also, it can confuse our opponent. } ( 12... c5 { would have worked with the bishop on b7 but here white has } 13. e4 $16 { 1-0 (21) So,W (2669) -Gundavaa,B (2472) Guangzhou 2010 } ) ( 12... dxc4 13. bxc4 ( 13. e4 $5 b5 ( 13... Re8 14. Nd2 $14 ) 14. bxc4 bxc4 $11 ) 13... Bxc4 14. Nd2 { can be a bit dangerous. } 14... Ba6 15. Qa4 Bb7 16. Qxa7 Ba8 17. Rac1 c5 $11 ) 13. e4 ( 13. h3 dxc4 { Now this is a very minutely better version for us. } 14. e4 ( 14. bxc4 Bxc4 15. Nd2 Ba6 16. Qa4 Bb7 17. Qxa7 Ba8 $11 { [%cal Gc6c5] } ) 14... Re8 15. Nd2 b5 16. bxc4 bxc4 17. Bf1 Bb4 $11 ) ( 13. Rac1 Re8 14. e4 dxc4 { The rook is worse on c1 here as the 'a' file is going to be open. } 15. Nd2 cxb3 16. axb3 b5 $11 ) 13... dxc4 14. Nd2 b5 { We should not open the 'a' file unnecessarily. The pawn on c4 is weak but white needs to put some effort to win it back. } ( 14... Nh5 $5 15. Be3 Nhf6 { I do not like to have such moves as my main line but it is certainly possible. } 16. Nxc4 b5 17. Ne5 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Nd7 $11 ) 15. bxc4 bxc4 16. Bf1 { A sad move to play, moving the bishop away from its ideal diagonal. } ( 16. Qa4 { this looks scary but we have } 16... Bb5 $1 17. Nxb5 Nb6 $1 18. Qxa7 cxb5 $17 ) ( 16. Na4 { runs into } 16... g5 $1 { We see the point behind the move h6. } 17. Be3 Ng4 18. Nf1 c5 $15 ( 18... Qc7 { 1/2-1/2 (72) Bareev,E (2666) -Vidit,S (2711) Batumi 2018 } ) ) 16... Bb4 { We are going after the e4 pawn. } 17. Nxc4 ( 17. a3 Ba5 18. Na4 ( 18. Bxc4 Bxc4 19. Nxc4 Bxc3 20. Qxc3 Nxe4 21. Qc2 f5 $11 { The light squares on the kingside are a liability for white. } ) 18... Bb5 19. Nxc4 Nxe4 20. Nab2 f5 { I do not want to misplace my knights. } ( 20... Ndf6 21. Be5 Bc7 22. Rac1 Ng5 23. Bg2 Nd5 24. a4 Ba6 25. Nd3 Nh7 26. Nc5 Bxc4 27. Qxc4 Nhf6 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (34) Hoebel,H (2396) -Reinecke,R (2307) ICCF email 2020 } ) 21. a4 Bxc4 22. Nxc4 Ndf6 $11 ) 17... Bxc4 18. Bxc4 Bxc3 { This is more in line with the variations we have seen so far. We win the important central pawn on e4. } ( 18... c5 $5 19. d5 Bxc3 20. Qxc3 e5 21. Bxe5 Nxe5 22. Qxe5 Re8 23. Qf5 g6 24. Qf3 Rxe4 25. Bf1 Qd6 $11 ) 19. Qxc3 Nxe4 20. Qa3 g5 { The bishop is forced to a worse square. } 21. Be5 Nd2 $1 { A nice tactical idea to equalise. We place our knight on an awkward square but it helps us activate our queen. } ( 21... Nxe5 22. dxe5 Qb6 23. Qf3 Nc5 24. h4 $16 ) 22. Be2 Nxe5 23. dxe5 Qd4 { We are already up a pawn and unless white does something immediately we are much better. } 24. Rac1 Rb8 25. Rc2 Rb1 { We manage to exchange the rooks just in time but our knight is misplaced in enemy territory. } 26. Rxb1 Nxb1 27. Qd6 ( 27. Qc5 Rd8 28. Qxd4 Rxd4 29. Rxc6 Nd2 30. Rc2 Kg7 $11 ) 27... Qe4 28. Bd3 Qf3 29. Be2 Qe4 30. Bd3 Qf3 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (30) Nyvlt,Z (2425) -Savoca,A (2458) ICCF email 2018 } ) 11... cxd5 12. Ne5 { Here we can go for the move Rc8 which will transpose to the next chapter. However, I am not recommending that as my main option there as it is very drawish in nature. Other choices like Bb7 and Nh5 also lead to a very solid position. We have a good independent option but it forces us to learn a bit of theory. Make your choice :) } 12... Nxe5 $5 ( 12... Rc8 { transposes to the next chapter. } ) ( 12... Nh5 13. Nc6 Rc8 14. Bc1 Qe8 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Nc3 { [%csl Gc1,Gg2] } 16... h6 $11 ) ( 12... Bb7 { is also passive giving up the bishop pair. } 13. Nc6 Bxc6 14. Qxc6 Qc8 15. Qb5 Qb7 16. Nc3 a6 ( 16... Rac8 17. Qd3 Nh5 18. Bd2 Nhf6 19. Rac1 $14 { 1/2-1/2 (51) Yu,Y (2729) -Xu,Y (2535) Danzhou 2016 } ) 17. Qd3 b5 18. e4 ( 18. Rac1 b4 19. Na4 Rfc8 $11 ) 18... dxe4 19. Nxe4 Nd5 20. Rac1 Nxf4 21. gxf4 Qb8 22. Ng5 Bxg5 23. fxg5 Ra7 $11 ) 13. dxe5 Ng4 { This is very scary to play over the board but a good weapon if we are well prepared. If you are not confident you can go for the more solid options on the previous move. } 14. h3 { The knight is trapped but we will look to make use of our lead in development. } ( 14. Bf3 g5 $1 ( 14... f5 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. Qa4 Bb7 17. Nd2 Qe8 18. Qxe8 Rfxe8 19. Nc4 Ba6 20. Ne5 Rac8 { 1/2-1/2 (29) Giri,A (2783) -Ding,L (2813) Wijk aan Zee 2019 } ) 15. Bxg4 ( 15. Qa4 Bc4 $1 16. b3 gxf4 17. Bxg4 b5 { The queen is in trouble on the queenside. } 18. Qa6 Bc5 19. bxc4 Qg5 20. Qxb5 Rac8 21. cxd5 fxg3 22. hxg3 f5 $1 23. Qb3 fxg4 $36 { The complications continue but white is the one at risk here. } ) 15... gxf4 16. Qa4 ( 16. gxf4 $4 Kh8 $19 ) ( 16. Nd2 f5 $1 17. exf6 Rxf6 $40 { [%csl Rg1][%cal Gg8h8] } ) 16... Bc4 $1 { We block the queen from swinging over to the kingside. } 17. Nd2 b5 18. Qc2 ( 18. Qa6 fxg3 19. hxg3 Bb4 20. Ne4 Qc7 21. Nf6+ Kg7 22. b3 ( 22. Nxd5 Bxd5 23. Rxd5 exd5 24. Qf6+ Kg8 25. Qg5+ Kh8 $11 ) 22... Rab8 $1 23. bxc4 Rb6 24. Qxb6 axb6 25. cxd5 Qxe5 { The position is dynamically balanced but I prefer black. } ) 18... Rc8 19. Nf3 Bxa2 $1 { We need this pawn to get our bishop to b3. } 20. Qd2 Bb3 21. Rdc1 Rc4 { This is a nice square for the rook and we would love to recapture with the 'd' pawn. } 22. gxf4 ( 22. Rxc4 dxc4 23. Qxf4 a5 24. h4 a4 25. Nd4 Qd7 $11 ) 22... Kh8 23. h3 Rg8 24. Kh2 a5 $11 { [%cal Ga5a4] } ) 14... Rc8 15. Nc3 ( 15. Qd2 g5 $1 { The dark-squared bishop is worth giving up our 'g' pawn for. } 16. hxg4 gxf4 17. gxf4 f6 { Let us open up the 'f' file. } ( 17... d4 $5 18. Na3 Bxa3 19. bxa3 Qh4 20. Bf3 Kh8 $11 ) 18. exf6 Rxf6 19. g5 Rg6 20. Nc3 Qf8 21. Rac1 h6 22. Nxd5 exd5 23. Qxd5+ Kh8 24. Rxc8 Bxc8 25. Qe5+ Qg7 $11 { white has to take a perpetual or risk getting worse. } ) 15... Nxf2 $1 { We are involving the white king into the game. } 16. Kxf2 Bc5+ 17. Be3 ( 17. Ke1 $2 f6 $15 ) 17... Bxe3+ 18. Kxe3 { Time is of the essence for us here. white just needs to get his king back to safety. } 18... b5 19. Qd2 ( 19. Qd3 Qb6+ 20. Qd4 { transposes. } ) 19... Qb6+ 20. Qd4 Qb8 $1 { Now the rook comes to c4 with a tempo. } 21. Kf2 ( 21. Qb4 Qb6+ 22. Kf3 Rc4 23. Qd6 Rc6 24. Qb4 f6 $5 ( 24... Rc4 $11 ) 25. g4 Rc4 26. Qe7 Rc7 27. Qb4 $11 ) 21... b4 22. Nb1 f6 $1 { We want to build a nice center to compensate for our missing piece. } 23. Qe3 fxe5+ 24. Kg1 Rc2 25. Nd2 e4 { There are different options for both sides here but the position is dynamically balanced. I will give some lines here but it has never been played before in OTB chess. } 26. Rab1 Qb6 { We trade the queens as it makes it easier to push our pawns down the middle of the board. Also,we are going after the e2 pawn. } ( 26... Bb5 27. Rdc1 Rfc8 28. Rxc2 Rxc2 29. Bf1 Qb6 30. Qxb6 axb6 31. e3 Ba4 32. b3 Be8 33. Nc4 dxc4 34. bxc4 Rxa2 35. Rxb4 Kf7 36. Rxb6 Rc2 37. h4 h6 38. g4 Kf6 39. Ra6 Ke7 40. Ra5 Bc6 41. Ra6 { 1/2-1/2 (41) Mason,I (2282) -Relyea,A (2331) ICCF email 2022 } ) 27. Qxb6 axb6 28. Bf1 e3 29. Nb3 Bxe2 30. Bxe2 Rxe2 31. Nd4 Ref2 { I feel white is risking more here as we can hardly lose with those pawns in the center. } 32. Rf1 Rd2 33. Nxe6 ( 33. Rxf8+ Kxf8 34. Nb3 Re2 35. Nd4 Rd2 36. Nb3 Rc2 { 1/2-1/2 (38) Korolev,A (2516) -Johnson,B (2529) ICCF email 2021 } ) 33... Re8 34. Ng5 e2 35. Rfe1 d4 36. Nf3 Rd3 37. Kg2 Ree3 38. Ng1 Rd2 39. Kf2 Re8 $11 *[Event "?"]
