1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Qc2 c6 9. Rd1 { This is one of the main moves in the position and is the natural square for the rook- the other rook is likely to come to c1 in the future. We can continue with our plan of developing the light-squared bishop. } 9... b6 10. Bf4 Ba6 11. Ne5 { [%csl Rc6][%cal Gg2c6,Gc4d5,Ge5c6] } 11... Rc8 { We are threatening to take on e5 now. } ( 11... Nxe5 { does not work right away } 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. e4 $14 ) 12. cxd5 { Now, we have a choice between the solid cxd5 and the more ambitious Nxd5. I recommend taking with the knight if you remember the details. If you feel like your opponent is very well prepared or do not remember any ideas you can take cxd5. } ( 12. Qa4 { looks tempting but white faces a lot of issues after the simple } 12... Nb8 $1 { [%cal Gd5c4,Ga6c4,Gb6b5] dxc4 followed by b5 is a big threat. } 13. Qb3 Nh5 $11 { [%csl Rc4][%cal Gf7f6] } ) ( 12. Nc3 { As usual this involves a pawn sacrifice to get the move e4. Here, we also manage to exchange our light-squared bishop. } 12... Bxc4 13. Nxc4 dxc4 14. e4 ( 14. b3 { A typical Catalan move to open up the 'a' file. However, the exchange of the light-squared bishops is in our favour. } 14... cxb3 15. axb3 a5 16. e4 Bb4 17. Na2 c5 $5 ( 17... Be7 18. Nc1 Nh5 19. Be3 g6 20. Nd3 Qc7 21. Rac1 Qb8 22. e5 c5 23. dxc5 bxc5 24. Qc3 Ng7 { 1/2-1/2 (26) Watkins, K (2297) -Kyhos, A (2283) ICCF email 2018 } ) 18. d5 e5 19. Bc1 Ne8 $11 { I think white has to work to prove his compensation. } ) 14... b5 { This position is dynamically balanced and let's try to understand the reason. white has the bishop pair and good control over the center. He can open up the 'a' file next. black has exchanged his worst bishop and is up a clean pawn. } 15. a4 { This makes more sense opening up the 'a' file first. } ( 15. d5 { A principled approach trying to open up the center. } 15... cxd5 16. exd5 e5 { We keep the center semi-closed. } ( 16... Qb6 $5 17. a4 ( 17. dxe6 fxe6 18. a4 a6 19. Qe2 Kh8 20. axb5 axb5 21. Bh3 Nc5 22. Be3 Rcd8 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 24. Bg2 h6 25. h3 e5 { 1/2-1/2 (40) Baranowiski Filho, M-Smith, R (1622) ICCF email 2019 } ) 17... b4 18. dxe6 fxe6 19. Nb5 Nd5 20. Bxd5 exd5 21. Rxd5 Nf6 22. Re5 Bc5 23. Qxc4+ Kh8 24. Qe2 a6 25. Re6 Bxf2+ 26. Kf1 Qb7 27. Nd6 Qh1+ 28. Kxf2 Qxa1 29. Rxf6 Rxf6 30. Nxc8 Qxa4 $11 ) 17. d6 ( 17. Bg5 Bc5 $11 { [%cal Gd8b6,Gc5d4] } ) ( 17. Be3 Bc5 ) 17... exf4 { The exchange of more pieces is definitely in our favour. } ( 17... Bxd6 18. Nxb5 Bc5 19. Bxe5 Bxf2+ 20. Qxf2 Ng4 21. Qxa7 $16 { This is a key difference compared to the main line. white wins a pawn here. } ) 18. Nxb5 $1 Rc5 19. dxe7 Qxe7 20. Nd6 fxg3 21. hxg3 Ne5 $11 { The position remains complex but we are still a pawn up. } ) 15... a6 16. axb5 axb5 17. d5 { white goes for the same break but there are some differences here. } ( 17. Ra7 Nb6 ) 17... cxd5 18. exd5 e5 19. Bg5 ( 19. d6 { is not so good here because } 19... Bxd6 20. Nxb5 Bc5 21. Bxe5 Bxf2+ 22. Qxf2 Ng4 $11 { leaves us with a promising position. Qa7 does not achieve anything here. } ) 19... Qb6 { There have been a lot of corr games here. } 20. Bh3 { creates a threat of taking on d7. } ( 20. Ne4 Bc5 21. Nxc5 Nxc5 22. d6 Nd3 23. Bxf6 gxf6 24. Be4 Rfd8 25. Qe2 ( 25. Bxd3 cxd3 26. Qxd3 Rc4 27. Qd5 Kg7 28. Ra3 Rc2 29. Qf3 Rxd6 30. Rxd6 Qxd6 31. Qg4+ Kf8 32. Ra8+ Ke7 33. Ra7+ { 1/2-1/2 (33) Wichert,G (2314) -Sitorus,Y (2434) ICCF email 2019 } ) 25... Kf8 26. Bxd3 cxd3 27. Rxd3 Rxd6 28. Rxd6 Qxd6 29. Qxb5 Rb8 30. Qc4 Qb4 { 1/2-1/2 (30) Cousins,R (2305) -Miettinen,K (2415) ICCF email 2019 } ) 20... Bc5 $1 { We are ready to give up an exchange in return for control over the dark squares. Our bishop will be very active on d4. } 21. Bxf6 Nxf6 22. Bxc8 Rxc8 { [%csl Gb5,Gc4,Rf2] } 23. Qf5 ( 23. Kg2 Bd4 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gc8d8] } ) 23... Re8 { We have excellent compensation for the exchange along the dark squares. } 24. d6 Qc6 25. Ra5 Bxd6 26. Rxb5 Bc5 27. Re1 h5 28. h3 ( 28. Rxe5 Rxe5 29. Qxe5 Bxf2+ ) 28... Bd4 29. Rexe5 Bxe5 30. Rxe5 Rxe5 31. Qxe5 g6 32. Qd4 Kg7 33. Qe5 Qf3 { 1/2-1/2 (33) Loinjak, S (2553) -Williamson, H (2529) ICCF email 2017 } ) 12... Nxd5 { [%cal Gd7e5] We attack the bishop on f4 and are also ready to take on e5. } ( 12... cxd5 13. Nc6 Nh5 14. Bc1 ( 14. Be3 Nb8 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Nc3 Nc6 ( 16... h6 17. Rac1 Nf6 18. Qd2 Nc6 19. h3 ) 17. Rac1 h6 18. Bf3 Nf6 19. Bf4 Rfd8 $11 ) 14... Nb8 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Qd2 ( 16. Nc3 Rfd8 17. h3 Nc6 18. g4 Nf6 19. Bg5 h6 20. Bh4 Na5 21. e3 Rd7 22. f3 Nc4 23. Qe2 e5 24. Bf2 Ne8 25. dxe5 Nc7 26. f4 Nxe5 27. Qc2 Nc4 28. e4 dxe4 29. Rxd7 Qxd7 30. Rd1 Qe7 { 1/2-1/2 (36) Faridani, A (2368) -Morrell,T (2308) ICCF email 2018 } ) 16... Nc6 17. b3 Rfd8 18. Bb2 h6 19. Nc3 Nf6 20. Rac1 Rc7 ( 20... Qd7 21. f3 Qe7 22. e3 Qe8 23. Ne2 Rd7 24. Nf4 Ne7 25. Rxc8 Qxc8 26. Rc1 Rc7 27. Rxc7 Qxc7 28. e4 { 1/2-1/2 (60) Matlakov,M (2710) -Alekseenko,K (2668) Izhevsk 2019 } ) 21. f3 Rdc8 22. e4 dxe4 23. fxe4 e5 $11 ) 13. Nc3 { Now the threat is to go Qa4. } ( 13. Nxc6 { does not work due to } 13... Nb4 14. Qa4 Nxc6 15. Bxc6 ( 15. Qxa6 $2 Nc5 $1 ( 15... Nb4 16. Qxa7 Nc2 17. Bb7 Nxa1 18. Bxc8 Qxc8 19. Rc1 ) 16. Qc4 Na5 17. Qc3 Na4 18. Qf3 Nxb2 $17 ) 15... Bxe2 16. Rc1 { so far it looks decent for white but we have } 16... Nb8 $1 17. Bg2 Rxc1+ 18. Bxc1 Qd7 19. Qxd7 Nxd7 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (24) Schott,R (2176) -Bartsch,R (2259) ICCF email 2018 } ) 13... Nxe5 { We want to trade the knight first before going after the dark-squared bishop. It has no way to escape our grasp. } ( 13... Nxf4 14. gxf4 Nxe5 15. fxe5 { might be dangerous. } ( 15. dxe5 { This is a good change in pawn structure for white but still playable. } ) ) 14. Bxe5 f6 15. Bf4 Nxf4 16. gxf4 f5 { [%cal Gg7g5,Gf8f6,Gf6h6] We want to now start our play with either g5 or Rf6 on the kingside. The dark squares are our main target. } 17. e3 { [%csl Rc6,Re6,Gg2] } ( 17. Qa4 Bb7 { This is an invitation to repeat moves, unfortunately. } 18. Qxa7 ( 18. e3 Kh8 { [%cal Gg7g5,Gf8g8] Our next moves are going to be g5 and Rg8. } 19. Rac1 Rg8 20. Qxa7 Qc7 21. h4 g5 $1 22. Nb5 Qd7 23. fxg5 Bxg5 $1 24. hxg5 Rxg5 25. f4 Rxg2+ 26. Kxg2 cxb5+ 27. Kf2 Ra8 28. Qxb6 Qd5 29. e4 Qxe4 30. d5 Qxf4+ 31. Ke1 Bxd5 $36 { 1/2-1/2 (31) Bruce, R (2040) -Asquith, J (2390) ICCF email 2022 } ) 18... Qc7 19. Nb5 ( 19. Rac1 { is met with } 19... Bh4 $1 20. Nb5 Bxf2+ 21. Kh1 Qd7 22. Nd6 Qxd6 23. Qxb7 Be3 $11 ) ( 19. Qa4 Qxf4 ) 19... Qd7 20. Nc3 { Happened in my game 1/2-1/2 (22) Nikolov, M (2508) -Arjun, K (2537) Cattolica 2021. Both sides cannot do much. } ) ( 17. Qb3 { We are happy to win up the pawn on e6 as it gives us a tempo to develop the rook to f6. } 17... Bd6 18. Qxe6+ Kh8 19. e3 Bb8 20. Rd2 g5 21. Ne2 Bxe2 22. Rxe2 gxf4 $11 ) ( 17. Rac1 Rc7 18. e3 { transposes. } ) 17... Rc7 { [%cal Ga6c8,Gg7g5,Gg8h8,Gc7g7,Gd8h4] We defend the pawn on a7 and the rook can also swing along the 2nd rank. } 18. Rac1 Kh8 19. Ne2 g5 { The direct approach to open the 'g' file. } ( 19... Bd6 $5 { [%cal Gg7g5] } 20. Ng3 h5 $1 { We would love for white to take on h5 and open the file for our rook. } 21. Kh1 ( 21. Nxh5 Qh4 22. Ng3 g5 $17 { [%cal Gc7h7] } ) 21... g5 22. Qc3 h4 $13 ) 20. fxg5 Bxg5 21. Kh1 Rg8 { We can continue with either Rg6-h6 or get our queen into the game with Bh6 and Qh4. The position is dynamically balanced with our weaknesses compensated by our play on the kingside. } 22. Rg1 ( 22. Bf3 Rg6 23. b4 Bh6 $11 { The queen is ready to jump to h4 next. } ) ( 22. b4 Bh6 23. f4 Bf8 24. Rg1 Bxb4 25. d5 Qf6 26. dxc6 Bc5 27. Nd4 Bxd4 28. exd4 Qxd4 29. Rcd1 Qxf4 { 1/2-1/2 (29) Perez Lopez,A (2412) -Genga,S (2423) ICCF email 2018 } ) 22... c5 23. Bf3 Rg6 { There are several different options here to play black. } 24. Ng3 f4 25. Ne4 fxe3 26. Nxg5 Rxg5 27. fxe3 Rxg1+ 28. Rxg1 cxd4 29. Qe4 Qf6 30. Qg4 Rg7 31. Qxg7+ Qxg7 32. Rxg7 Kxg7 33. exd4 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (35) Halliwell, T (2397) -Anokhin, Y (2417) ICCF email 2018 } *[Event "?"]
