1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 { I believe that this is the best move order to go for the Nd2 variation as it cuts down on our options. It does allow some other ideas on move 3 though. } ( 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nbd2 { allows us to go } 5... dxc4 { followed by a quick b5. I do not recommend this as we cannot do it in the 3.g3 move order. } ) 3... d5 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5. Nd2 { This is a more aggressive option as white is often ready to sacrifice the c4 pawn for play on the kingside and the center. } 5... O-O ( 5... dxc4 $4 { The first time that I prepared this opening I forgot to check the 3.g3 move order. Once, I reached this position I released to my horror that I could not do this anymore. } 6. Qa4+ $18 ) 6. Nf3 ( 6. a3 Bxd2+ 7. Bxd2 dxc4 8. Nf3 { transposes to the main line. } ) 6... dxc4 ( 6... b6 { is a more solid option but I like to go for the critical lines. } ) 7. a3 { This forces us to give up our bishop on d2 but is also a non-developing move. } 7... Bxd2+ 8. Bxd2 Nc6 { We immediately go after the pawn on d4. We have to play concretely here as we have some passive pieces and the worse pawn structure. } ( 8... Bd7 $5 9. Rc1 Bc6 10. Rxc4 Bd5 11. Rc1 h6 12. O-O Nc6 13. e3 a5 14. Qe2 a4 15. Rfd1 Bb3 16. Re1 Bd5 17. Bc3 Ne4 18. Qc2 f5 19. Nd2 Nxd2 20. Qxd2 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Rf7 22. Qe2 Ne7 23. f3 Qd7 { 1/2-1/2 (56) Nakamura,H (2736) -Carlsen,M (2855) chess24.com INT 2021 } ) 9. e3 b5 { This may look scary to play but there is no danger yet along the diagonal. } ( 9... Rb8 { is not necessary } 10. Qc2 b5 11. b3 Rb6 12. bxc4 bxc4 13. O-O { [%csl Ra7,Rc4,Rc7] } ) 10. b3 ( 10. O-O Bb7 11. a4 a6 12. b3 cxb3 13. Qxb3 Ne7 { We will go Bd5 next and we have managed to activate the usual 'bad' bishop. } 14. axb5 Rb8 { We are greedy as usual and want to keep an extra pawn. } ( 14... Bd5 15. Qb2 axb5 16. Bb4 Re8 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19. Qxb5 c6 20. Qb6 Nd7 21. Qc7 Qd8 22. Qxd8+ Rxd8 23. Rd1 Ra8 { 1/2-1/2 (23) Swiatek,J (2101) -Nimylovych,T (2000) FICGS email 2022 } ) 15. Bb4 axb5 16. Ne5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Rb7 18. Rfc1 Re8 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. Ra5 b4 21. Rc4 Ne4 $11 { white is the one who has to be careful here with the passed 'b' pawn. } ) 10... Bb7 { Our goal here is to activate the light-squared bishop and maybe trade our weak c7 pawn with c5 soon. } 11. bxc4 ( 11. a4 $2 { 1/2-1/2 (90) Abasov,N (2632) -Karjakin,S (2760) Douglas 2019 } 11... b4 $1 12. bxc4 a5 $17 { [%cal Gc6e7,Gc7c5] } ) ( 11. O-O Ne7 12. bxc4 bxc4 { tr } ) 11... bxc4 12. O-O { The threat now is to go Ne5 and take control over the long diagonal. } ( 12. Rc1 { is quite greedy with the king still on e1. } 12... Ne7 13. Rxc4 a5 { white is not able to castle right now. We have to play dynamically here using our lead in development. } 14. Rc5 { white provokes the move Ne4 as it blocks the long diagonal. } ( 14. Rc1 Qd6 { [%csl Ra3] We will get the queen to a6 as the bishop is doing very well on b7. } 15. O-O ( 15. a4 Qa6 16. Bf1 Qd6 $11 ) 15... Qxa3 16. Ra1 Qd6 17. Bxa5 Be4 $11 { [%cal Ge7c6,Gd6d5] white will have to trade the light-squared bishops at some point and it is completely even. } ) 14... Ne4 15. Rc1 c5 $14 { We take the chance to liquidate our weak pawn on c7. } ( 15... Qd6 16. Ng5 $1 { [%csl Rb7] } ) ( 15... Bd5 { is also fine but has been already been played once. } 16. O-O Qd6 17. Ne5 Qxa3 18. Ra1 Qb2 19. Bxa5 Ng6 20. Qb1 { 1/2-1/2 (37) Yu,Y (2762) -Le,Q (2728) Danzhou 2018 } ) 16. Ng5 ( 16. dxc5 Rc8 17. Ng5 Nxc5 18. Bxb7 Nxb7 $11 ) 16... Nd6 $1 { Of course we want to trade the bishops. Now, white has some weaknesses on the kingside. } 17. Bxb7 Nxb7 18. Qf3 Rb8 19. dxc5 h6 20. Nh3 Qd3 { We again stop him from castling kingside. Now we will bring our rook into the game next. } ( 20... Qc7 21. O-O Nxc5 $11 ) 21. c6 ( 21. Nf4 Qxa3 22. O-O Nxc5 23. Bc3 Nf5 $11 ) 21... Nd6 22. Nf4 Qxa3 ( 22... Qa6 { is also possible but he can go } 23. Qe2 { forcing us to move our queen away. } 23... Qa8 24. O-O { the position is still equal. } 24... Nxc6 $11 ) 23. O-O Rfc8 24. c7 Rb7 { We will win the c7 pawn soon. } ( 24... Rb5 25. Rfd1 e5 26. Nh5 Ne8 27. h4 Rc5 28. Ra1 Qb3 29. Bxa5 Nxc7 { 1/2-1/2 (39) Giesel,M (2067) -Cumming,D (2306) ICCF email 2017 } ) 25. Ra1 Qb3 26. Bxa5 Nc4 27. Rfd1 Nxa5 28. Rd8+ Kh7 29. Qe4+ g6 30. Qe5 Qb2 31. Qxb2 Rxb2 32. Rxc8 Nxc8 33. Rxa5 Rc2 $11 { After mass simplifications we reach an equal endgame. } ) 12... Ne7 { We immediately stop that and open the diagonal for the bishop. c5 is another plan to keep in mind. } 13. Qc2 a5 $1 { It is a useful move on the queenside and we prepare the move Ba6 if needed. Also, it stops the move Bb4, especially when we continue with c5 and Rc8-c5. } ( 13... c5 14. Qxc4 cxd4 15. Qxd4 Qxd4 16. Nxd4 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Rfc8 18. Rfc1 h6 { 1/2-1/2 (30) Harikrishna,P (2713) -Anton Guijarro,D (2697) Prague 2020 } 19. Bb4 Ned5 20. Nc6 { with still some slight pressure } ) ( 13... Bd5 $5 14. Bb4 c5 15. Bxc5 Ne4 16. Bxe7 ( 16. Bb4 a5 $11 ) 16... Qxe7 17. Ne5 Nd6 $11 18. e4 Bb7 19. Rfe1 Rac8 20. d5 Rc5 21. Nd3 Rb5 22. Nb4 exd5 23. exd5 Qf6 $11 ) 14. Rfe1 ( 14. Rfd1 Ra7 $1 { The queen will go to a8 putting pressure along the diagonal. } 15. Qxc4 Qa8 16. Qe2 Rc8 ( 16... Ba6 { is a way to repeat moves. } 17. Qe1 Bb7 $11 ) 17. Rdc1 Be4 18. Ra2 c5 19. dxc5 Rac7 $11 { black has the initiative here with more active pieces. } ) 14... c5 { We eliminate our weak pawn. } 15. Qxc4 ( 15. dxc5 Rc8 16. e4 ( 16. Bc3 Be4 $17 ) 16... Rxc5 17. Bc3 Ng6 $11 { white has to show his compensation for the pawn. } ) 15... Ne4 ( 15... cxd4 { is possible if we want to go into an endgame immediately but there is no hurry. } 16. Qxd4 Qxd4 17. Nxd4 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Ne4 19. Red1 Rfb8 $11 ) 16. Red1 Nxd2 { We get rid of the bishop pair and the resulting position is completely equal. } 17. Rxd2 cxd4 18. Qxd4 Qc7 19. Qe5 Rac8 20. Qxc7 Rxc7 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (20) Cirulis,I (2253) -Ozen,B (2257) LSS email 2023 } *[Event "?"]
