1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5. Nd2 O-O 6. Nf3 dxc4 7. O-O { This is a very natural move but it allows us to secure the pawn on b5. It leads to messy positions but I generally prefer to be the side with an extra pawn. } 7... b5 8. a4 ( 8. b3 { This is a common idea in the Catalan but does not work so well with the knight on d2. } 8... c3 9. Nb1 Bb7 10. a3 Be4 $1 { A surprising intermediate move with a huge threat of c2. } 11. Qe1 ( 11. Ne1 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 $15 ) 11... c2 12. Nc3 Bxc3 13. Qxc3 Nc6 $11 { Not an easy task to win back the pawn for white. } ) ( 8. Ne5 Nd5 9. Qc2 { This has been played by Dubov a few times but in online rapid and blitz. } ( 9. a3 Bd6 { This is a better square for the bishop keeping an eye on the e5 knight. } 10. b3 Bb7 11. Ne4 ( 11. bxc4 Bxe5 12. dxe5 Nc3 $11 ) 11... cxb3 12. Qxb3 a6 13. Ng5 Be7 $11 ) 9... f6 $1 { This is not a move you go for when you are not prepared. We kick the knight back at the cost of weakening our king. } 10. Nef3 a5 { This is a nice prophylactic move. We anticipate the move a4 and c6 after which we may have to retreat to b6. So we stop him from possibly going a5. At the same time it also gains some space on the queenside. } 11. b3 ( 11. a4 c6 12. e4 Nb6 $17 ) 11... cxb3 12. Nxb3 Be7 $11 { We can continue with Qe8 and a4 next. I do not see enough compensation for the pawn. } ) 8... c6 { We defend the b5 pawn comfortably. white is unable to create anything on the queenside. He has to try and create some play on the kingside. } ( 8... Ba6 9. Qc2 Bxd2 10. Nxd2 $14 ) ( 8... c3 9. Nb3 cxb2 10. Bxb2 bxa4 11. Ne5 Nd5 12. Rxa4 $14 ) 9. Ne1 { white brings his knight to c2 kicking the bishop back and keeping an eye on the d4 pawn. The immediate threat is to take on b5. } ( 9. Ne5 { does not achieve anything. } 9... Nd5 10. e4 ( 10. Ne4 f6 ) 10... Nc7 11. Nb1 Bb7 12. Nc3 a6 $15 { We can go Nd7 next and trade off the knights. } ) ( 9. Qc2 a5 { transposes to another chapter. } ) ( 9. axb5 { Is tempting to fully open the diagonally but white cannot exploit it as we always have the move Nd5. } 9... cxb5 10. Ng5 Nd5 11. e4 Nc7 12. Nxh7 $1 { Having gone for Ng5, white has to justify the aggression. He cannot just retreat. Our pieces are clumped on the queenside. } 12... Kxh7 13. e5 ( 13. Qh5+ { is a big mistake as we can go } 13... Kg8 14. e5 f5 $1 15. Bxa8 ( 15. exf6 Qxf6 $17 ) 15... Nxa8 16. Rxa7 Bd7 $1 17. Rxa8 Bc6 { white is under huge trouble on the long diagonal. } 18. Ra7 Be8 19. Qd1 Qxd4 $17 ) 13... g6 { We stop ideas of Qh5. The dark squares are weak but our bishop will do a good defensive job on e7. } 14. Bxa8 Nxa8 15. Qf3 Bd7 16. Ne4 Be7 17. Rxa7 Nc6 18. Qf4 { Very important again to go on the offensive. } 18... Kg8 ( 18... Nxa7 19. Qh6+ Kg8 20. Ng5 Bxg5 21. Bxg5 $16 ) 19. Rd1 $1 { Another only move to keep d4 under control. } 19... Nxa7 20. Qh6 Be8 21. Bg5 f5 22. exf6 Rxf6 $11 { The position is objectively balanced but there are a lot of complications on the board. } ) 9... Nd5 { We block the diagonal and also remove the knight from f6 where it may come under fire in the future. } ( 9... Ba6 { is another option to take on b5 with the bishop. } 10. Nc2 Be7 11. axb5 Bxb5 12. Nb1 $1 Nbd7 13. Nc3 ( 13. Bd2 a5 { 1/2-1/2 (46) Dubov,D (2666) -Yu,Y (2737) Moscow 2016 } ) 13... Nd5 ( 13... Qb6 14. e4 { [%csl Gd4,Ge4] } ) 14. Nxb5 ( 14. e4 Nxc3 15. bxc3 a5 16. e5 a4 17. Qg4 $44 { [%cal Gg2e4,Gg4h3] } ) 14... cxb5 15. e4 Nb4 ( 15... N5b6 16. e5 Nd5 17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Ne3 $44 { [%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] } ) 16. Nxb4 Bxb4 17. e5 a5 18. Qg4 { [%cal Gc1h6] } 18... Re8 19. Bg5 Qb6 20. Rad1 Ra7 ( 20... Rac8 21. h4 a4 22. h5 Bf8 ) 21. h4 $44 { [%cal Gh4h5] } ) 10. Nc2 ( 10. e4 Nb6 11. a5 ( 11. axb5 cxb5 $15 ) ( 11. e5 bxa4 12. Ne4 N8d7 13. Bg5 Be7 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Nd6 Ba6 $11 { We can always go Nc8 and kick the knight out of d6. } ) 11... N6d7 { The a5 pawn cannot be protected and white needs to create something quick. } 12. e5 Bxa5 { We will just take the pawn and bring the bishop back to e7. white cannot really do much. } ( 12... Bb7 { was unnecessary in the game: 1/2-1/2 (44) Wang,H (2709) -Ding,L (2777) Huaian 2017 } ) 13. Ne4 Bb4 14. Qh5 ( 14. Bg5 Be7 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 $15 { 1/2-1/2 (38) Dimitrov,D (2380) -Davidov,A (2332) ICCF email 2018 } 16. Nd6 Nb6 ) 14... a5 $1 { This is a very important move actually. Let's see why. } ( 14... -- { I am adding a null move to showcase the point. } 15. Ng5 h6 16. Be4 f5 17. Nxe6 Qe8 18. Qxe8 Rxe8 19. Nc7 fxe4 20. Nxe8 $16 ) 15. Ng5 ( 15. g4 f6 $15 ) 15... h6 16. Be4 f5 17. Nxe6 Qe8 18. Qxe8 Rxe8 19. Nc7 fxe4 20. Nxe8 Na6 { We can continue with Nb6-d5 next. Our queenside pawns give us the edge here. } 21. Nd6 Nb6 22. Nxe4 Bh3 23. Ng2 a4 $15 { This may not look like a big advantage but our play on the queenside is very hard to stop. } ) 10... Be7 ( 10... Bxd2 11. Bxd2 Bb7 ( 11... f5 12. Ne3 $44 ) 12. e4 Ne7 { 1/2-1/2 (31) Papaioannou,I (2592) -Nielsen,P (2681) Eretria 2011 } 13. Ne3 Qxd4 ( 13... a5 14. Qh5 { [%csl Rb5] } ) 14. axb5 cxb5 15. Bb4 Qxd1 16. Rfxd1 Nec6 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 18. f4 $14 ) 11. e4 Nf6 { Both knight moves are possible but I feel this gives white more chances to go wrong. } ( 11... Nc7 12. e5 Nd5 { tr } ) 12. e5 ( 12. d5 $14 b4 $1 { We want to take on d5 now and any capture with the d pawn develops our pieces. } ( 12... cxd5 13. axb5 $11 ) 13. Nxc4 cxd5 14. exd5 Nxd5 $11 ) ( 12. g4 { is very logical but runs into } 12... e5 $1 13. h3 ( 13. g5 Nfd7 14. Nf3 a5 $15 { [%csl Rg5] } ) 13... Nfd7 $1 { We remove our knight from the kingside and it feels like white is the one with a lot of weaknesses there. } 14. Nf3 b4 15. a5 Ba6 16. dxe5 b3 17. Ncd4 Nc5 $15 { The knight is heading for the juicy d3 square. } ) 12... Nd5 13. Ne4 b4 { Our plan is to go Nd7, a5 and Ba6 next followed by an eventual c3. white on the other hand has to do something on the kingside. } ( 13... Nd7 14. axb5 cxb5 15. Nc3 N7b6 16. Nxb5 Bb7 17. Qg4 { [%csl Ge5] } ) ( 13... Bb7 14. Qg4 Kh8 15. Bg5 $14 ) 14. Qg4 Kh8 15. Ne3 ( 15. Qh5 Nd7 16. Ng5 Bxg5 17. Bxg5 Qe8 { Our position is very solid here and there is nothing to be afraid of on the kingside. We can go for the move f6 next exchanging the queens. } 18. Qh4 a5 { It is so easy to play for us. We will next go Ba6 and try to go c3. } ( 18... Rb8 19. Ne3 ( 19. Rac1 Ba6 20. Rfe1 f6 $15 { 1/2-1/2 (48) Narkun,M-Sonnenfeld,W (1877) ICCF email 2017 } ) 19... Ba6 20. Rfe1 c3 21. bxc3 Nxc3 22. Be7 b3 23. Nd1 Ne2+ 24. Kh1 Nxd4 25. Bxf8 Nc2 26. Bxg7+ Kxg7 27. Be4 Nxe1 28. Qxh7+ Kf8 29. Nb2 $11 ) 19. Ne3 Ba6 20. Rfc1 { white has to focus on winning the pawn back on the queenside. } 20... Nxe3 21. fxe3 ( 21. Bxe3 f5 22. exf6 ( 22. Bxc6 Rc8 $17 ) 22... Nxf6 $11 { [%cal Gf6d5] } ) 21... f6 22. exf6 Nxf6 23. Rf1 Qg6 $11 { The position is dynamically balanced here at high depth but black is on the better side for sure. } ) 15... Ba6 { [%cal Gc4c3] } ( 15... Nxe3 16. Bxe3 $14 ) 16. Rd1 Nd7 17. Bf1 c5 $1 { We are looking to undermine white's control over the center and moreover the f3 square is a weakness to exploit right now. } 18. Nxd5 exd5 19. Nd6 { white has to atleast try and win our dark-squared bishop. } 19... Bxd6 ( 19... cxd4 20. Nf5 Rg8 21. Qxd4 Bb7 $11 ) 20. exd6 Nf6 21. Qf4 cxd4 22. Rxd4 Re8 { white's initiative has disappeared and he has to make sure that he does not get much worse. } 23. Bd2 Rb8 ( 23... Qa5 24. d7 Red8 25. Bh3 Bb5 26. Qe5 Bxd7 27. Bxd7 Nxd7 28. Qf5 Qb6 29. Rxd5 Nf6 30. Rb5 Qd4 31. Bxb4 Qxb2 $11 ) 24. Bg2 c3 25. bxc3 b3 { The b pawn is quite dangerous in the endgame. } 26. Bxd5 Nxd5 27. Rxd5 Bb7 28. Rb5 Bc6 29. c4 Qd7 30. Rxb8 Rxb8 31. Bc3 f6 $11 { black definitely has the upper hand here seeing the weaknesses in white's kingside. } *[Event "?"]
