1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5. Nd2 O-O 6. Nf3 dxc4 7. Qc2 { The queen is well placed here along this diagonal and also keeps an eye on the c4 pawn. } 7... a5 $1 { We prepare the move b5 as now a4 can be met with c6. We create some space for our rook. } ( 7... b5 8. a4 $14 ) 8. a3 ( 8. Qxc4 { is too ready } 8... b6 { [%csl Re1][%cal Gc8a6] } 9. a3 Be7 10. Ne5 Ra7 11. Ndf3 Ba6 12. Qc2 c5 13. Bf4 ( 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Nd3 { 1/2-1/2 (30) Donchenko,A (2568) -Wojtaszek,R (2741) Germany 2016 } 14... Rc7 $15 { [%csl Re1] } ) 13... cxd4 14. Rd1 { 1/2-1/2 (52) Sengupta,D (2586) -Wei,Y (2732) Chengdu 2017 } 14... Rc7 15. Qb1 Nd5 16. Nxd4 Nxf4 17. gxf4 Bd6 18. O-O h6 $11 ) ( 8. O-O b5 9. a4 ( 9. a3 Be7 10. a4 c6 11. e4 Na6 12. e5 Nb4 13. Qb1 Nfd5 { 1/2-1/2 (28) mitrabhaa (2741) -SenseiJulio (2662) Chess.com 2020 } ) 9... c6 10. b3 cxb3 11. Nxb3 Ba6 12. Nc5 Nbd7 $11 ) 8... Bxd2+ { We cannot afford to waste a tempo and retreat here. } ( 8... Be7 { Was a bad decision in my first game in this line. I did not understand the position well. } 9. Nxc4 b6 { 1-0 (46) Mitrabha Guha-Arjun Kalyan Chess.com 2020 [Kalyan,Arjun] } 10. Bg5 $1 Bb7 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. O-O { [%cal Gf1d1,Gf3g5] } 12... g6 13. Rfd1 $14 ) 9. Bxd2 b5 { This is similar to the previous chapter but here the difference is that white has not yet committed his king to the kingside. He has the chance to create an attack there. } 10. a4 { This is one of the most critical tries here to fight for an edge. white wants us to close our queenside after which he can create something on the kingside. } ( 10. Ne5 Ra6 11. a4 c6 $11 ) ( 10. b3 Bb7 { We give up the pawn to develop the bishop to its best diagonal. This is similar to our main line but a much better version since we do not damage our pawn structure. } ( 10... cxb3 { is also possible but I do not want to be so greedy here. We value our development and piece activity more. } 11. Qxb3 c6 12. Rc1 ( 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Rfd1 Qe7 14. Rac1 Bb7 $11 ) 12... Ba6 13. O-O b4 14. Rfe1 bxa3 15. Qxa3 Bb5 16. e4 Nbd7 17. d5 cxd5 18. exd5 Nxd5 19. Nd4 Qb6 $11 ) 11. bxc4 Be4 12. Qc3 { The queen needs to keep control over both d4 and c4. } ( 12. Qc1 Nc6 $11 ) 12... b4 { We get a passed pawn on the queenside which can turn out to be very dangerous in the endgame. } 13. Qb2 Nc6 { The d4 pawn is under a lot of fire. } 14. axb4 axb4 15. O-O ( 15. Rxa8 { allows us to take control over the queenside after } 15... Qxa8 16. O-O Qa3 $17 ) 15... h6 { This is a useful move clearing the backrank and covering g5. } 16. Bxb4 ( 16. Be3 Qd6 $11 ) 16... Rb8 17. Ra4 Nxb4 18. Rxb4 Rxb4 19. Qxb4 Bxf3 20. Bxf3 Qxd4 { The position is equal but I do prefer the queen and knight combo. } ) 10... Bb7 $1 { I came across this move a couple of years back and got a chance to play it in the Sitges Open 2022. This is the active approach getting our bishop to the long diagonal at the cost of the b5 pawn. Unfortunately, it has been played a few times by now. } ( 10... c6 { is the overwhelming main line. It was also my intention for a very long time but the lines are very concrete and there is a lot to remember. white has several ways to make a forced draw if he feels like it. Feel free to check them out. } 11. h4 ( 11. O-O Bb7 12. Rfd1 Nbd7 13. b3 cxb3 14. Qxb3 b4 { 0-1 (43) Socko,B (2642) -Sargsyan,S (2628) Warsaw 2021 } ) ( 11. e4 h6 ( 11... e5 12. dxe5 Nfd7 13. e6 $1 ( 13. Be3 Na6 14. O-O Ndc5 15. Rfd1 Qc7 16. axb5 cxb5 17. Nd4 Rb8 { 1/2-1/2 (23) Tomashevsky,E (2702) -Ding,L (2774) Palma de Mallorca 2017 } ) 13... fxe6 14. e5 $14 ) 12. g4 ( 12. O-O Bb7 13. Rfe1 ( 13. e5 Nd5 14. Qc1 Nd7 15. Bxh6 gxh6 16. Qxh6 Qe7 17. Ng5 f6 18. Qg6+ Qg7 19. Qxg7+ ) 13... Nbd7 14. e5 Nd5 15. Qe4 f5 $1 16. exf6 Qxf6 17. axb5 cxb5 18. Rxa5 b4 19. Rxa8 Bxa8 20. Qxe6+ Qxe6 21. Rxe6 c3 $44 ) 12... Nh7 $1 ( 12... e5 13. g5 ( 13. dxe5 Nh7 14. Be3 Na6 15. O-O Nb4 16. Qc3 Bxg4 17. Nd4 Qc8 18. axb5 cxb5 19. f4 Nd3 20. Qc2 b4 21. b3 Bh3 22. Bxh3 Qxh3 23. Rf3 Qc8 24. Nf5 Kh8 25. Bd4 Nc5 26. bxc4 Ne6 27. Be3 a4