7. Ra3 Be4 ( 17... cxd4 18. Bxg4 fxg4 19. Rxg4 d3 20. Qxc4 Bxf3 21. exf3 Qf6 ) 18. Qxc4 Bd5 19. Qc2 cxd4 20. Bxg4 Rc8 21. Qd3 fxg4 22. Rxg4 Bxf3 23. Rxg7+ Kxg7 24. Qg6+ Kh8 25. Qxh6+ Kg8 26. Qg6+ Kh8 27. Qh6+ ) 17... fxg4 18. Rxg4 ( 18. Nh2 cxd4 19. Qxc4 Qb6 20. Rxg4 Rf7 ) 18... Bxf3 19. exf3 cxd4 ( 19... Nf6 20. Rg6 $13 ( 20. Rxg7+ Kxg7 21. Qg6+ Kh8 22. Qxh6+ Nh7 23. dxc5 Rxf3 24. O-O-O Qf6 25. c6 Rb3 26. Qxf6+ Nxf6 27. Bc3 Kg7 28. Rd7+ Kh6 29. Bxf6 Rxb5 30. c7 Rc8 31. Be7 c3 32. bxc3 a4 33. Bd6 Rb7 34. Rd8 Rbxc7 35. Bxc7 Rxc7 36. Kd2 Rf7 37. c4 a3 38. Ra8 Rxf2+ 39. Kc3 a2 40. c5 e5 41. Kd3 Kxh5 42. Ke4 Rc2 43. Kxe5 Rxc5+ ) 20... cxd4 21. Bxh6 ( 21. Qxc4 Kh8 ) ( 21. O-O-O d3 22. Qc3 Kh7 23. Qe5 Qd5 24. Qc7 Qd7 25. Qe5 Qd5 ) 21... Nxh5 22. O-O-O ( 22. Qxc4 Qh4 23. Qxe6+ Kh7 24. O-O-O Rae8 25. Qb6 Rb8 26. Qe6 Rbe8 $11 ) 22... d3 23. Qc3 Rf6 24. Bg5 Qe8 25. Rxf6 gxf6 26. Bxf6 Kf7 27. Be5 Qxb5 28. Qd4 Qd5 29. Qe3 a4 30. Rh1 a3 31. bxa3 c3 32. Bxc3 Rxa3 33. Qd4 Qxd4 34. Bxd4 Nf4 $11 ) 20. Bxh6 Rf7 21. O-O-O ( 21. Rxd4 Qb6 22. Be3 Qxb5 23. O-O-O Ne5 24. h6 Nd3+ 25. Kb1 Rb8 26. Bc1 Qb3 27. Rg1 Nxc1 28. Kxc1 Qxc2+ 29. Kxc2 Rfb7 ) 21... Ne5 22. Rgxd4 ( 22. Rdxd4 Qb6 23. Bxg7 Nxg4 24. Rxg4 Rxg7 25. Rxg7+ Kxg7 26. Qg6+ Kh8 27. Qf6+ Kg8 28. Qg6+ Kf8 29. Qf6+ ) 22... Qe8 23. Kb1 Qxb5 24. Be3 Rb8 25. Bf4 Rxf4 26. Rxf4 Nd3 27. Rd4 Qe5 28. R1xd3 cxd3 29. Qxd3 Qxh5 ) 11. axb5 ( 11. Bg5 $14 Nc6 { This has the dual purpose of both attacking the pawn on d4 and getting to the b4 square. } ( 11... c6 { is also good but I do not like it by principle. } 12. e4 Na6 13. e5 Nb4 14. Qe2 h6 15. Bh4 g5 16. Bxg5 Nd3+ 17. Kf1 hxg5 18. exf6 Qxf6 19. h4 g4 20. Ne5 bxa4 $11 ) 12. O-O Nb4 { We keep it simple, planting our knight on the b4 outpost. } ( 12... Nxd4 { is very interesting } 13. Nxd4 Bxg2 14. Rfd1 Be4 15. Qc1 h6 $1 { We give up the queen but get a lot of material in return. } 16. Nf5 hxg5 17. Rxd8 Rfxd8 18. Ne3 c6 $44 { The position is dynamically balanced here. } ) 13. Qc1 bxa4 14. Rxa4 ( 14. Rd1 h6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11 ) 14... h6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Ne5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Qf5 $11 { The position is likely to simplify soon. } ) 11... Qd5 { white cannot defend the pawn on b5 but at the same time our pawn on c4 is very weak and is likely to fall soon. } 12. O-O ( 12. Nh4 { does not make much sense here misplacing the knight. } 12... Qxb5 13. Bxb7 Qxb7 14. O-O Ne4 15. Nf3 Nd6 16. Bxa5 h6 17. Rfc1 Nc6 $11 ) 12... Qxb5 13. Qa4 { white wants to trade the queens having the bishop pair. We cannot afford that so easily as the c4 pawn is very weak. } ( 13. Ne5 $14 { Exchanges typically favour us here with the extra pawn. } 13... Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Qd5+ 15. Kg1 Nc6 16. Nxc6 Qxc6 17. Rxa5 ( 17. Ra4 Ne4 18. Bf4 Nd6 $11 { white can take on d6 and basically agree to a draw. } ) 17... Rxa5 18. Bxa5 h5 { The light squares on the kingside are going to be a concern for white. } 19. Rc1 Qb7 $11 ) ( 13. Rfc1 { This has been played in a few games recently. } 13... Bd5 { Once we get the bishop to d5 followed by Nc6 we are doing very well. } 14. Ne5 { white has to trade the bishops or go for the move e4. } 14... Nc6 15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. f3 { This is a principled move preparing to go e4 next. } ( 16. Bxd5 { This exchange improves our pawn structure and white has to be careful to make a draw. } 16... exd5 17. b3 Qe6 18. bxc4 Qxe2 19. Bg5 Qe6 20. Bxf6 Qxf6 21. cxd5 Qxd4 $11 ) 16... Qb6 17. e4 { Was played by Magnus. } ( 17. Qc3 $2 { was played in the game 1-0 (56) Srihari,L (2384) -Khayrullin,D (2343) Budapest 2023 and it is a serious error due to } 17... e5 18. e3 e4 $17 { black gets a huge edge due to the light squares. } ) ( 17. Bc3 $5 { Happened in the game 1-0 (62) Dubov,D (2710) -Tabatabaei,M (2692) Samarkand 2023. } 17... Bc6 18. e4 a4 { The bishop will go to b5 next. e5 can always be met with Nd5. The position remains complex as white can try to create some play on the kingside. } 19. Be1 Bb5 20. Bf2 Qb7 21. Bf1 Rfb8 { It is roughly equal with our extra pawn compensated by the bishop pair. } ) 17... Qxd4+ 18. Kh1 Bc6 $1 { We need the 'b' file open for our rook. } ( 18... Bb7 19. Bxa5 Qe5 20. Bc3 { white had some minute pressure and he went on to win a complex game 1-0 (66) Carlsen,M (2861) -Keymer,V (2693) chess24.com INT 2022 } ) 19. Bxa5 Rfb8 20. Qc3 ( 20. Bc3 Qc5 $11 ) 20... Qxc3 21. Bxc3 Nd7 $11 { white will not be able to win the pawn back easily and we have no weaknesses. } ) 13... Qa6 { This was a novelty when I analysed it but has been played already now. } ( 13... Qxa4 { is a big inaccuracy. } 14. Rxa4 Nbd7 15. Rxc4 $16 { 1/2-1/2 (67) Predke,A (2650) -Sarana,A (2655) Izhevsk 2019 } ) 14. Qxa5 ( 14. Rac1 Bd5 $15 ) ( 14. Rfc1 { allows us to liquidate our weakness with } 14... c3 15. Rxc3 Qxe2 16. Bf1 Qe4 17. Bg2 Qe2 18. Re1 Qa6 19. Rec1 Qe2 $11 ) 14... Qc6 15. Qc5 { white is determined to trade queens but here we have the chance to weaken his pawn structure. } ( 15. Qc3 Nbd7 16. Rac1 Nb6 $11 ) ( 15. Qb4 Nbd7 16. b3 ( 16. Rac1 Ra4 $15 ) 16... cxb3 17. Qxb3 Qb6 18. Qxb6 cxb6 19. Nh4 Bxg2 20. Nxg2 h5 { The endgame is completely even. } ) 15... Qxc5 16. dxc5 Nbd7 { It is not going to be easy to defend both the 'c' pawns. } 17. Nd4 ( 17. Bb4 { The bishop is not so well placed here. } 17... Rfb8 18. Rxa8 Bxa8 19. Ba3 Bxf3 20. Bxf3 g5 $11 { This is a typical move in such endgames gaining space on the kingside. white on the other hand usually goes for the move h4 to gain space. } ) ( 17. Be3 Ne4 18. Rac1 ( 18. Nd2 { allows } 18... Nxd2 19. Bxd2 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 Nxc5 { We can take the pawn without any worries. } 21. Bb4 Nb3 22. Rxa8 Rxa8 $11 ) 18... Bd5 19. c6 { We need the bishop on d5 to maintain control over the c4 pawn. white has the bishop pair and we need to be careful. } ( 19. Rfd1 Nexc5 20. Nd2 Ra4 21. Bf4 { white is preparing the move e4 and it looks dangerous but we can just go } 21... Rb8 22. e4 e5 $1 { We are creating the e6 square for the bishop. } 23. exd5 exf4 24. Nxc4 fxg3 $11 ) 19... Ndc5 20. Nd4 ( 20. Ng5 Nxg5 21. Bxc5 Rfb8 22. Be3 f6 $11 { The knight can return easily next. } ) 20... Rfb8 21. Ra1 Nb3 { We exchange the knights after which c6 will fall. } 22. Rxa8 Rxa8 23. Bxe4 Bxe4 24. f3 Nxd4 25. Bxd4 Bxc6 $11 ) 17... Bxg2 18. Kxg2 h5 $1 { We clear the back rank and gain space on the kingside. Now we can take on c5 next. } 19. Bb4 { The bishop is forced to defend the pawn awkwardly. } ( 19. Rfc1 { allows } 19... Rxa1 20. Rxa1 Nxc5 21. Bb4 Nb3 22. Nxb3 Rb8 $11 ) 19... Rfc8 ( 19... Ne5 { happened in the game 1-0 (31) Esipenko,A (2682) -Keymer,V (2686) Biel 2022 but it gives white some chances after } 20. Ba5 $14 ) 20. c6 ( 20. Rfc1 Nd5 21. c6 Ne5 22. Bc3 g5 $11 { We can go g4 next and get a bind on the kingside. } ) 20... Nb6 21. Rfc1 Rxa1 22. Rxa1 Nbd5 23. Be1 ( 23. Bc3 Ne4 $11 ) 23... Rb8 { It is not easy to defend b2 and also c6. } 24. Bc3 Ne4 25. Ra7 Rb6 26. Kf3 Ng5+ ( 26... Nexc3 27. bxc3 e5 $11 ) 27. Kg2 Ne4 $11 { Both sides can try to continue but a repetition is a fair result. Our pawn on h5 helps restrict the white king. } *[Event "?"]
