1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 { This position can occur via the Catalan with Bb4+ or the Nimzo. There are many ways for black to equalise but we need to be well prepared as we are entering Catalan territory which may be new for a few players. } 4... O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. Nf3 { Definitely the Catalan way of playing, giving up the c4 pawn for activity and space in the center. } ( 6. cxd5 { This shows a bad understanding of the opening as the bishop is now staring at a very solid central formation. } 6... exd5 7. Nf3 c6 8. O-O Re8 9. a3 Bf8 10. Qc2 Nbd7 $11 { We can get our knight to e4 next. Another plan is to go Nb6, Be6 followed by Qc8 and Bh3. } ) ( 6. a3 { This non-developing move has been played by a few strong players. white is afraid that we would take on c4 and then retreat with the bishop. } 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 dxc4 { We always take the bait when offered. We should go for either the c5 or e5 break as quickly as possible. } 8. Nf3 ( 8. Qa4 { white brings the queen out too early and gives us the chance to develop our pieces with a tempo. } 8... Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 { This is a common theme in the Catalan. The light-squared bishop is well known to be black's worst piece and we would love to exchange it. } 10. f3 { This is a non-developing move and it weakens several squares. } ( 10. Nf3 Bd5 11. Qd3 Be4 { Let the queen run back from where it came from. } 12. Qb5 ( 12. Qd1 c5 $15 ) 12... a6 13. Qb2 b5 $11 { The knight is coming to b6 soon and white is in trouble. } ) 10... Nbd7 11. e4 Nb6 12. Qa2 ( 12. Qd3 Nfd7 $15 { [%cal Gd7c5] The other knight is ready to come to c5 and white is in trouble. } ) 12... Bb5 13. Bf1 Ba4 $11 { We want to go Rc8 and c5 next. } ) 8... c5 9. O-O ( 9. Ne5 { white is too eager to win back the pawn. } 9... cxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. cxd4 Nc6 $1 { A common resource in the Catalan as black is ready to give up a pawn to free up his queenside. } 12. Nxc4 ( 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bxc6 Rb8 14. Bf4 Rb6 $15 { [%cal Gc8b7,Gc8a6] } ) 12... Nxd4 13. Rb1 Bd7 $11 14. Bb2 Nc2+ 15. Kd2 Ba4 $15 { black went on to win in the game 0-1 Froewis, G (2432) -Svane, R (2573) Minsk 2017. } ) 9... cxd4 10. Qxd4 { This was famously played by Magnus in his loss to Niemann in the Sinquifield Cup 2022 which sparked all of the drama. } ( 10. cxd4 Bd7 { We bring the bishop to c6 in order to trade the light-squared bishops. } 11. Qc2 ( 11. Ne5 Bc6 12. Bxc6 Nxc6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bg5 c5 $11 ) 11... Bc6 12. Qxc4 Bd5 $11 { Our next move will be Nc6 and the position is balanced. } ) 10... Nc6 { Why not follow Niemann who was still well prepared? } ( 10... Qxd4 11. Nxd4 Nd5 $11 { [%cal Gb8c6] } ) 11. Qxc4 e5 12. Bg5 h6 13. Rfd1 { This was a bailout move by Magnus but the resulting endgame is not without dangers. } ( 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11 ) 13... Be6 14. Rxd8 Bxc4 15. Rxa8 Rxa8 16. Bxf6 gxf6 $11 { Should have been a draw but madness ensued in the game 0-1 (57) Carlsen, M (2861) -Niemann, H (2688) Saint Louis 2022. } ) 6... dxc4 7. O-O Nc6 { The knight usually goes to d7 or we play c5 and Nc6. However, in Catalan, we need to both stop Ne5 and keep an eye on the d4 pawn. } 8. Qa4 { white creates a threat of Ne5 and he can go Qb5 next to win the pawn on c4. } ( 8. Ne5 { is not a great pawn sacrifice. } 8... Nxd4 9. Nxc4 Nc6 $11 ) ( 8. Bg5 { The exchange of the dark-squared bishop for the knight on f6 is another idea from the Catalan. white is following the colour strategy- he is playing on the light squares here and the dark-squared bishop is not necessary. } 8... h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. e3 Rb8 { We will see this move several times preparing the move b5. The rook gets out of any trouble along the long diagonal. } 11. Ne4 ( 11. Nd2 Na5 { [%cal Gb7b5] Yet another benefit of the knight on c6. } 12. Qa4 Qe7 $17 ) 11... Qg6 12. Ned2 b5 { We will not give up the pawn so easily. } 13. a4 Qh5 14. axb5 Qxb5 15. Qc2 e5 $11 { We will get our light-squared bishop out now and white has to be careful playing against the bishop pair. } ) ( 8. a3 Be7 { If given the choice we would love to bring the bishop back especially when we have an extra pawn. } 9. e4 a6 { It is not going to be easy to get the pawn back for white. He has to try and prove his compensation in the center or the kingside. } 10. Be3 ( 10. Bf4 { This has been played a few times but it does not achieve much. } 10... b5 11. Qe2 ( 11. Qd2 { Was played by Radjabov but it has a clear drawback. } 11... Na5 $1 12. Rad1 { black was much better in the game 0-1 (29) Radjabov, T (2765) -Aronian, L (2781) Paris 2021 after } 12... Nb3 13. Qe2 Bb7 $17 ) ( 11. d5 exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 Na5 $15 { There is still no compensation for the pawn. } ) 11... Bb7 12. Rad1 Na5 { The knight heads to b3 and we want to play c5 soon. } 13. h4 Nb3 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bf4 { Happened in the game 1-0 (28) Halkias, S (2581) -Lenderman, A (2614) St Petersburg 2012 and black could have maintained his big advantage with } 15... Re8 $17 { [%cal Ge7f8] We the tuck the bishop followed by Nd7 and c5. } ) 10... b5 11. h4 { white's plan is to go e5 followed by Ng5. } ( 11. Qe2 Bb7 12. Rad1 Na5 $15 ) 11... Rb8 12. e5 Nd5 13. Ng5 Bxg5 14. Bxg5 Nce7 $11 { We maintain control over the d5 square. white has to give up his bishops if he wants to win back the pawn. } ) 8... Nd5 9. Qc2 Be7 { We retreat with the bishop to get the b4 square for the knight anticipating the move e4. } 10. Rd1 ( 10. a3 { This looks clever to cover the b4 square but it leaves a big hole on b3. } 10... Na5 11. Rb1 Bd7 12. e4 Nxc3 13. Qxc3 b6 $15 { [%cal Ga8c8,Gd7b5,Gc7c5] } ) 10... Rb8 { We get the rook out of the dangerous h1-a8 diagonal and prepare the move b5. } 11. e4 ( 11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 c6 $11 { We keep the d5 square secure. The pin is not a big deal now since we have the move Nb4. } ) 11... Ncb4 ( 11... Ndb4 { is also possible but I want to keep the option to take on c3. } ) 12. Qd2 ( 12. Qe2 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nd3 $11 { [%cal Gc7c5] black is doing very well with c5 to follow. } ) ( 12. Qb1 { white anticipates the opening of the 'b' file but even in the best-case scenario, white wins back the pawn and nothing else. } 12... Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nd3 14. Qb5 Nxc1 { We eliminate a key minor piece. } 15. Raxc1 Bd7 16. Qxc4 c5 { All our plans have been executed well. } 17. Ne5 ( 17. dxc5 Qc7 $15 ) 17... b5 18. Qe2 Be8 $11 { We can go c4 and start pushing our pawns on the queenside. } ) 12... Nxc3 { Exchanging of pieces favour us here as we have less space. } 13. Qxc3 b5 14. b3 Bb7 $1 { We win a tempo against the e4 pawn and force white to make some concession. } ( 14... cxb3 15. Qxb3 { white has very good compensation here as we are forced to retreat with our knight. } ) 15. Ne1 { [%csl Gd3][%cal Ga2a3] white covers the d3 square and is threatening to go a3 next. } ( 15. a3 { allows the simple } 15... Nd3 16. bxc4 Nxc1 { We win the bishop pair and also the pawn on e4. Now white is fighting for equality. } 17. Rdxc1 Bxe4 18. Ne5 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Rb6 20. cxb5 Rxb5 $11 { white will probably win back the pawn but we have nothing to worry about. } ) 15... cxb3 16. axb3 ( 16. Qxb3 a5 { Our pawns are quite dangerous on the queenside. } 17. Bf4 Qd7 18. Rab1 a4 19. Qc3 { white is trying to tempt us into taking the pawn on a2 as he can then trap the knight. } 19... Nxa2 $1 { We do it anyway as our pawns are more than enough compensation for the piece. } 20. Qd2 b4 21. Qxa2 b3 22. Qe2 Bc6 $15 { white has to play very precisely to survive here. } ) 16... Ra8 17. Bb2 { The threat here is to go d5 and we have to act prophylactically. } 17... Bd6 $11 { We are ready to meet d5 with e5 and I do not see a clear way for white to equalise. } *[Event "?"]
