{How to continue here?} 10... Nh5 $1 {This is a frequent response when white has blocked the retreat for the bishop.} 11. e3 {This has been played a few times by Anish Giri. white is ready to give up the dark-squared bishop but wants to improve his pawn structure.} (11. cxd5 Nxf4 $1 12. dxc6 Nxg2 13. cxd7 Qxd7 14. Kxg2 Bb7 $44 {We have tremendous compensation with the unopposed bishops.}) (11. Be5 Bb7 12. cxd5 (12. e4 Rc8 13. Rfe1 g5 $36 {[%csl Re5] Now f6 is a big threat.}) 12... exd5 {This is the more fighting option and it works well here because the bishop is on e5.} (12... cxd5 {is also okay but more passive.} 13. Rfc1 Rc8 $11) 13. e4 Rc8 14. Rfe1 (14. Qa4 a6 15. exd5 cxd5 16. Qb3 f6 17. Bf4 Nxf4 18. gxf4 Bd6 $11) 14... c5 $1 {We open up the position for our pieces. We can win the dark-squared bishop at our leisure.} 15. exd5 cxd4 16. Qd3 Bxd5 $11) (11. Be3 Bb7 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Rfc1 Nhf6 (13... Bd6 14. Bg5 f6 15. Be3 f5 16. Bg5 Qe8 17. e3 h6 18. Bf4 Nxf4 19. exf4 Nf6 $11) 14. Bf4 Rc8 15. Qd1 Rxc1 16. Rxc1 Qa8 $11) 11... Bb7 {Now we are threatening the move g5 trapping the bishop.} (11... g5 $6 12. Be5 f6 13. cxd5 $16) 12. cxd5 exd5 (12... Nxf4 {is the more tempting move but there is no hurry yet. We want to keep the idea of g5 in the air.} 13. exf4 cxd5 14. Rfc1 Bd6 (14... Rc8 15. Qd1 Rxc1 16. Rxc1 Qb8 $11 {0-1 (58) Giri,A (2764) -Van Foreest,J (2682) chess24.com INT 2020}) 15. Bf1 Nf6 16. Bd3 Qe7 17. Re1 Rfc8 (17... Rac8 18. Qd1 Qd8 19. Qe2 Rc7 20. a3 g6 21. Ne5 Qe7 22. h4 Rfc8 23. Rad1 Qf8 24. Qf3 Nh5 25. Nf1 Ng7 26. Ne3 {1-0 (51) Giri,A (2731) -Anand,V (2751) Zagreb, Croatia 2021} h5 $11) 18. Qd1 Qd8 19. Ne5 Rc7 20. h4 g6 21. Qe2 h5 22. Rac1 Rac8 23. Rxc7 Rxc7 24. Kg2 Qe8 25. Ndf3 Ne4 $11) 13. h4 {white wastes a move to stop the idea of g5.} (13. Rac1 g5 $5 (13... c5 $11) 14. g4 Nxf4 15. exf4 f5 $5 {Having the bishop pair we can look to create something on the kingside, especially on the dark squares.} 16. gxf5 gxf4 $11 {[%cal Gc6c5,Ge7f6]}) 13... c5 {As we are going to win the bishop pair soon it makes sense to try and open the position.} 14. Nb1 {The knight is better placed on c3 but it also wastes valuable time allowing us to bring all our pieces into the game.} (14. Rfe1 Re8 15. Rac1 (15. Rad1 Rc8 $11) 15... Rc8 16. Qd1 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Rxc1 18. Qxc1 Nxf4 19. exf4 Bc5 $11) 14... Nxf4 (14... b5 $5 15. Ng5 g6 16. Nc3 cxd4 17. Nxd5 Rc8 18. Qd3 Bxd5 19. Bxd5 Ndf6 20. Bb3 dxe3 21. Qxe3 Bc5 22. Qf3 Nxf4 23. Qxf4 a5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (50) Tinjaca Ramirez,L (2388) -Jakubcin,M (2437) ICCF email 2021}) 15. exf4 cxd4 16. Nxd4 Rc8 17. Nc3 Bb4 {We will create a weakness on c3 and bring our knight to e4 next.} 18. Rfd1 (18. Rad1 Re8 {This is more precise it seems compared to the direct Nf6 but it is too deep.} (18... Nf6 19. Ndb5 a6 20. Qb3 {[%csl Rd5]} Bc5 {should still be fine.}) 19. Ndb5 Bxc3 20. bxc3 Nf6 21. Nxa7 Rc5 $11 {[%csl Ra7]}) 18... Nf6 19. Qa4 (19. Ndb5 a6 20. Qb3 Bc5 $11 {f2 is a big problem here.}) 19... a5 {b5 square is not something that white can exploit.} 20. Rac1 Rc4 21. Qb5 Qc7 22. Bf1 Rc5 23. Qd3 Ne4 24. Ncb5 Qd8 25. Rb1 Rc4 26. b3 Rc8 $11 *


