{How to continue here?} 15... Nxf2 $1 {We are involving the white king into the game.} 16. Kxf2 Bc5+ 17. Be3 (17. Ke1 $2 f6 $15) 17... Bxe3+ 18. Kxe3 {Time is of the essence for us here. white just needs to get his king back to safety.} b5 19. Qd2 (19. Qd3 Qb6+ 20. Qd4 {transposes.}) 19... Qb6+ 20. Qd4 Qb8 $1 {Now the rook comes to c4 with a tempo.} 21. Kf2 (21. Qb4 Qb6+ 22. Kf3 Rc4 23. Qd6 Rc6 24. Qb4 f6 $5 (24... Rc4 $11) 25. g4 Rc4 26. Qe7 Rc7 27. Qb4 $11) 21... b4 22. Nb1 f6 $1 {We want to build a nice center to compensate for our missing piece.} 23. Qe3 fxe5+ 24. Kg1 Rc2 25. Nd2 e4 {There are different options for both sides here but the position is dynamically balanced. I will give some lines here but it has never been played before in OTB chess.} 26. Rab1 Qb6 {We trade the queens as it makes it easier to push our pawns down the middle of the board. Also,we are going after the e2 pawn.} (26... Bb5 27. Rdc1 Rfc8 28. Rxc2 Rxc2 29. Bf1 Qb6 30. Qxb6 axb6 31. e3 Ba4 32. b3 Be8 33. Nc4 dxc4 34. bxc4 Rxa2 35. Rxb4 Kf7 36. Rxb6 Rc2 37. h4 h6 38. g4 Kf6 39. Ra6 Ke7 40. Ra5 Bc6 41. Ra6 {1/2-1/2 (41) Mason,I (2282) -Relyea,A (2331) ICCF email 2022}) 27. Qxb6 axb6 28. Bf1 e3 29. Nb3 Bxe2 30. Bxe2 Rxe2 31. Nd4 Ref2 {I feel white is risking more here as we can hardly lose with those pawns in the center.} 32. Rf1 Rd2 33. Nxe6 (33. Rxf8+ Kxf8 34. Nb3 Re2 35. Nd4 Rd2 36. Nb3 Rc2 {1/2-1/2 (38) Korolev,A (2516) -Johnson,B (2529) ICCF email 2021}) 33... Re8 34. Ng5 e2 35. Rfe1 d4 36. Nf3 Rd3 37. Kg2 Ree3 38. Ng1 Rd2 39. Kf2 Re8 $11 *


