{How to continue here?} 13... a5 $1 {It is a useful move on the queenside and we prepare the move Ba6 if needed. Also, it stops the move Bb4, especially when we continue with c5 and Rc8-c5.} (13... c5 14. Qxc4 cxd4 15. Qxd4 Qxd4 16. Nxd4 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Rfc8 18. Rfc1 h6 {1/2-1/2 (30) Harikrishna,P (2713) -Anton Guijarro,D (2697) Prague 2020} 19. Bb4 Ned5 20. Nc6 {with still some slight pressure}) (13... Bd5 $5 14. Bb4 c5 15. Bxc5 Ne4 16. Bxe7 (16. Bb4 a5 $11) 16... Qxe7 17. Ne5 Nd6 $11 18. e4 Bb7 19. Rfe1 Rac8 20. d5 Rc5 21. Nd3 Rb5 22. Nb4 exd5 23. exd5 Qf6 $11) 14. Rfe1 (14. Rfd1 Ra7 $1 {The queen will go to a8 putting pressure along the diagonal.} 15. Qxc4 Qa8 16. Qe2 Rc8 (16... Ba6 {is a way to repeat moves.} 17. Qe1 Bb7 $11) 17. Rdc1 Be4 18. Ra2 c5 19. dxc5 Rac7 $11 {black has the initiative here with more active pieces.}) 14... c5 {We eliminate our weak pawn.} 15. Qxc4 (15. dxc5 Rc8 16. e4 (16. Bc3 Be4 $17) 16... Rxc5 17. Bc3 Ng6 $11 {white has to show his compensation for the pawn.}) 15... Ne4 (15... cxd4 {is possible if we want to go into an endgame immediately but there is no hurry.} 16. Qxd4 Qxd4 17. Nxd4 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Ne4 19. Red1 Rfb8 $11) 16. Red1 Nxd2 {We get rid of the bishop pair and the resulting position is completely equal.} 17. Rxd2 cxd4 18. Qxd4 Qc7 19. Qe5 Rac8 20. Qxc7 Rxc7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (20) Cirulis,I (2253) -Ozen,B (2257) LSS email 2023} *

